{"title_page": "Hughes School District", "text_new": "'''Hughes School District 27'''  was a public school district based in [[Hughes, Arkansas]], [[Education in the United States|United States]] until it closed in Summer 2015 due to declining enrollment.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Hughes Arkansas Schools ordered to merge with West Memphis School District|url = http://wreg.com/2015/04/10/hughes-arkansas-schools-ordered-to-merge-with-west-memphis-school-district/|website = WREG.com|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n\nThe school district encompassed {{convert|226.21|mi2|km2}} of land in [[St. Francis County, Arkansas|St. Francis County]] and [[Crittenden County, Arkansas|Crittenden County]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usa.com/school-district-0508010.htm |title=Hughes School District |publisher=USA.com |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> It included Hughes, [[Horseshoe Lake, Arkansas|Horseshoe Lake]], and the St. Francis County section of [[Jennette, Arkansas|Jennette]].<ref name=StFrancisschmap>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/sch_dist/st05_ar/c05123_st_francis/DC10SD_C05123_001.pdf|title=SCHOOL DISTRICT REFERENCE MAP (2010 CENSUS): St. Francis County, AR|publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2018-05-14}} Note: Since the production of the map, the Hughes School District merged into the West Memphis school district in 2015</ref><ref name=Crittendenschmap>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/sch_dist/st05_ar/c05035_crittenden/DC10SD_C05035_001.pdf|title=SCHOOL DISTRICT REFERENCE MAP (2010 CENSUS): Crittenden County, AR|publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2018-05-14}} Note: Since the production of the map, the Hughes School District merged into the West Memphis school district in 2015</ref>\n\n==History==\nUnder Arkansas law Act 60,<ref name=Superville>{{cite web|author=Superville, Denisa R.|url=https://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/2017/06/07/when-a-community-loses-its-schools.html|title=When a Community Loses Its Schools|work=[[Education Week]]|date=2017-06-07|accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref> the state can forcefully merge a school district which has fewer than 350 total students for a consecutive period of two years with another school district. The Hughes district had, in the 2012-2013 and 2013-2014 school years, 348 students and 344 students, making it eligible to be merged.<ref name=Edboard>{{Cite news|title = Ed Board votes to consolidate Hughes, West Memphis districts|url = http://arkansasnews.com/news/arkansas/ed-board-votes-consolidate-hughes-west-memphis-districts|work = [[Arkansas News]]|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref> As the state determined that the district had financial problems, it was not eligible to apply for a waiver to stay open under House Bill 1263.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lesnick, Gavin|url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2015/apr/09/hughes-school-district-consolidated-west-memphis/|title=Hughes School District consolidated into West Memphis |work=[[Arkansas Online]]|date=2015-04-09|accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2014\u20132015 school year the Hughes district created a petition asking for a consolidation with the [[Forrest City School District]], but the Forrest City district stopped supporting the petition. On April 9, 2015, the [[Arkansas Board of Education]] voted to consolidate the Hughes district with the [[West Memphis School District]].<ref name=Edboard/>\n\n== Schools ==\nThe schools' mascot and athletic emblem was the ''Blue Devil'' with royal blue and white as the school colors.\n* Mildred Jackson Elementary School, served prekindergarten through grade 6.\n* [[Hughes High School]], served grades 7 through 12.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.hsd4.org/|title=Hughes School District}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/*/http://hughes.grsc.k12.ar.us/|title=Hughes School District}}\n{{Defunct school districts in Arkansas}}\n[[Category:Education in Crittenden County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Education in St. Francis County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Defunct school districts in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:School districts disestablished in 2015]]\n{{arkansas-school-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Hughes School District 27'''  was a public school district based in [[Hughes, Arkansas]], [[Education in the United States|United States]] until it closed in Summer 2015 due to declining enrollment.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Hughes Arkansas Schools ordered to merge with West Memphis School District|url = http://wreg.com/2015/04/10/hughes-arkansas-schools-ordered-to-merge-with-west-memphis-school-district/|website = WREG.com|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n\nThe school district encompassed {{convert|226.21|mi2|km2}} of land in [[St. Francis County, Arkansas|St. Francis County]] and [[Crittenden County, Arkansas|Crittenden County]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usa.com/school-district-0508010.htm |title=Hughes School District |publisher=USA.com |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> It included Hughes, [[Horseshoe Lake, Arkansas|Horseshoe Lake]], and the St. Francis County section of [[Jennette, Arkansas|Jennette]].<ref name=StFrancisschmap>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/sch_dist/st05_ar/c05123_st_francis/DC10SD_C05123_001.pdf|title=SCHOOL DISTRICT REFERENCE MAP (2010 CENSUS): St. Francis County, AR|publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2018-05-14}} Note: Since the production of the map, the Hughes School District merged into the West Memphis school district in 2015</ref><ref name=Crittendenschmap>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/sch_dist/st05_ar/c05035_crittenden/DC10SD_C05035_001.pdf|title=SCHOOL DISTRICT REFERENCE MAP (2010 CENSUS): Crittenden County, AR|publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2018-05-14}} Note: Since the production of the map, the Hughes School District merged into the West Memphis school district in 2015</ref>\n\n==History==\nUnder Arkansas law Act 60,<ref name=Superville>{{cite web|author=Superville, Denisa R.|url=https://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/2017/06/07/when-a-community-loses-its-schools.html|title=When a Community Loses Its Schools|work=[[Education Week]]|date=2017-06-07|accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref> the state can forcefully merge a school district which has fewer than 350 total students for a consecutive period of two years with another school district. The Hughes district had, in the 2012-2013 and 2013-2014 school years, 348 students and 344 students, making it eligible to be merged.<ref name=Edboard>{{Cite news|title = Ed Board votes to consolidate Hughes, West Memphis districts|url = http://arkansasnews.com/news/arkansas/ed-board-votes-consolidate-hughes-west-memphis-districts|publisher = [[Arkansas News]]|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref> As the state determined that the district had financial problems, it was not eligible to apply for a waiver to stay open under House Bill 1263.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lesnick, Gavin|url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2015/apr/09/hughes-school-district-consolidated-west-memphis/|title=Hughes School District consolidated into West Memphis |work=[[Arkansas Online]]|date=2015-04-09|accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2014\u20132015 school year the Hughes district created a petition asking for a consolidation with the [[Forrest City School District]], but the Forrest City district stopped supporting the petition. On April 9, 2015, the [[Arkansas Board of Education]] voted to consolidate the Hughes district with the [[West Memphis School District]].<ref name=Edboard/>\n\n== Schools ==\nThe schools' mascot and athletic emblem was the ''Blue Devil'' with royal blue and white as the school colors.\n* Mildred Jackson Elementary School, served prekindergarten through grade 6.\n* [[Hughes High School]], served grades 7 through 12.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.hsd4.org/|title=Hughes School District}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/*/http://hughes.grsc.k12.ar.us/|title=Hughes School District}}\n{{Defunct school districts in Arkansas}}\n[[Category:Education in Crittenden County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Education in St. Francis County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Defunct school districts in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:School districts disestablished in 2015]]\n{{arkansas-school-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WhisperToMe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hughes_School_District"}
{"title_page": "Supercar Street Challenge", "text_new": "{{Infobox VG\n|title = Supercar Street Challenge\n|image = \n|caption =\n|developer = [[Exakt Entertainment]]\n|publisher = [[Activision]]\n|designer =\n|series = \n|engine =\n|released = {{vgrelease|NA|October 22, 2001 <small>(PS2)</small>|NA|October 30, 2001 <small>(PC)</small>|EU|November 30, 2001}}\n|genre = [[Racing video game|Racing]], [[Simulation video game]]\n|modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n|platforms = [[PlayStation 2]], [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]\n}}\n\n'''''Supercar Street Challenge''''' is a [[racing video game]] developed by [[Exakt Entertainment]] and published by [[Activision]] for [[PlayStation 2]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] in 2001.\n\n==Gameplay==\nIn this game, the player has the power to design, build, and race their own dream car. They can choose their car from the Saleen S7 to the Lotus Concept Vehicle M220 to the Callaway C12; customize their own vehicle in the Steve Saleen Styling Studio; and race down the environments in London, Paris, Monaco, Los Angeles, Munich, Rome, and Turin.<ref name=NGen/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| PC = true\n| PS2 = true\n| na = true\n| Fam_PS2 = 26/40<ref name=Fam>{{cite web |url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=6785&redirect=no |title=\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30ab\u30fc \u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8 \u30c1\u30e3\u30ec\u30f3\u30b8 [PS2] |language=Japanese |website=[[Famitsu]] |publisher=[[Enterbrain]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| GSpot_PC = 3.9/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Osborne |first=Scott |date=November 14, 2001 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/supercar-street-challenge-review/1900-2824627/ |title=Supercar Street Challenge Review (PC) [date mislabeled as \"May 17, 2006\"] |website=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| GSpot_PS2 = 5.8/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Ahmed |first=Shahed |date=October 26, 2001 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/supercar-street-challenge-review/1900-2820564/ |title=Supercar Street Challenge Review (PS2) [date mislabeled as \"May 17, 2006\"] |website=GameSpot |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| IGN_PC = 4.9/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Kittur |first=Niki |date=November 13, 2001 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2001/11/14/supercar-street-challenge |title=Supercar Street Challenge (PC) |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| IGN_PS2 = 5.7/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Edwards |first=Ralph |date=October 24, 2001 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2001/10/24/supercar-street-challenge-2 |title=Supercar Street Challenge (PS2) |website=IGN |publisher=Ziff Davis |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| NGen_PS2 = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=NGen>{{cite magazine |last=Steinberg |first=Scott |url=https://archive.org/details/NextGen85Jan2002/page/n83/mode/2up |title=Supercar Street Challenge (PS2) |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |publisher=[[Future US|Imagine Media]] |issue=85 |date=January 2002 |page=82 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC_PC = 45/100<ref name=MCPC>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/supercar-street-challenge |title=Supercar Street Challenge for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC_PS2 = 57/100<ref name=MCPS2>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-2/supercar-street-challenge |title=Supercar Street Challenge for PlayStation 2 Reviews |website=Metacritic |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe PlayStation 2 version received \"mixed\" reviews, while the PC version received \"generally unfavorable reviews\", according to the [[Review aggregator|review aggregation]] website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=MCPC/><ref name=MCPS2/> Scott Steinberg of ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' said the former console version had \"Standard automotive thrills with a mildly amusing twist \u2013 vehicle design options.\"<ref name=NGen/> In Japan, where said console version was ported and published by [[Success (company)|Success]] on November 21, 2002, ''[[Famitsu]]'' gave it a score of 26 out of 40.<ref name=Fam/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{moby game|id=/supercar-street-challenge}}\n\n[[Category:2001 video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:Racing video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n\n{{vg-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox VG\n|title = Supercar Street Challenge\n|image = \n|caption =\n|developer = [[Exakt Entertainment]]\n|publisher = [[Activision]]\n|designer =\n|series = \n|engine =\n|released = '''PlayStation 2'''<br />{{vgrelease|NA|October 22, 2001|EU|November 30, 2001}}\n|genre = [[Racing video game|Racing]], [[Simulation video game]]\n|modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n|platforms = [[PlayStation 2]], [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]\n}}\n\n'''''Supercar Street Challenge''''' is a [[racing video game]] developed by [[Exakt Entertainment]] and published by [[Activision]] for [[PlayStation 2]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] in 2001.\n\n==Gameplay==\nIn this game, the player has the power to design, build, and race their own dream car. They can choose their car from the Saleen S7 to the Lotus Concept Vehicle M220 to the Callaway C12; customize their own vehicle in the Steve Saleen Styling Studio; and race down the environments in London, Paris, Monaco, Los Angeles, Munich, Rome, and Turin.<ref name=NGen/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| PC = true\n| PS2 = true\n| na = true\n| Fam_PS2 = 26/40<ref name=Fam>{{cite web |url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=6785&redirect=no |title=\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30ab\u30fc \u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8 \u30c1\u30e3\u30ec\u30f3\u30b8 [PS2] |language=Japanese |website=[[Famitsu]] |publisher=[[Enterbrain]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| GSpot_PC = 3.9/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Osborne |first=Scott |date=November 14, 2001 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/supercar-street-challenge-review/1900-2824627/ |title=Supercar Street Challenge Review (PC) [date mislabeled as \"May 17, 2006\"] |website=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| GSpot_PS2 = 5.8/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Ahmed |first=Shahed |date=October 26, 2001 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/supercar-street-challenge-review/1900-2820564/ |title=Supercar Street Challenge Review (PS2) [date mislabeled as \"May 17, 2006\"] |website=GameSpot |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| IGN_PC = 4.9/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Kittur |first=Niki |date=November 13, 2001 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2001/11/14/supercar-street-challenge |title=Supercar Street Challenge (PC) |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| IGN_PS2 = 5.7/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Edwards |first=Ralph |date=October 24, 2001 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2001/10/24/supercar-street-challenge-2 |title=Supercar Street Challenge (PS2) |website=IGN |publisher=Ziff Davis |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| NGen_PS2 = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=NGen>{{cite magazine |last=Steinberg |first=Scott |url=https://archive.org/details/NextGen85Jan2002/page/n83/mode/2up |title=Supercar Street Challenge (PS2) |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |publisher=[[Future US|Imagine Media]] |issue=85 |date=January 2002 |page=82 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC_PC = 45/100<ref name=MCPC>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/supercar-street-challenge |title=Supercar Street Challenge for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC_PS2 = 57/100<ref name=MCPS2>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-2/supercar-street-challenge |title=Supercar Street Challenge for PlayStation 2 Reviews |website=Metacritic |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe PlayStation 2 version received \"mixed\" reviews, while the PC version received \"generally unfavorable reviews\", according to the [[Review aggregator|review aggregation]] website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=MCPC/><ref name=MCPS2/> Scott Steinberg of ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' said the former console version had \"Standard automotive thrills with a mildly amusing twist \u2013 vehicle design options.\"<ref name=NGen/> In Japan, where said console version was ported and published by [[Success (company)|Success]] on November 21, 2002, ''[[Famitsu]]'' gave it a score of 26 out of 40.<ref name=Fam/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{moby game|id=/supercar-street-challenge}}\n\n[[Category:2001 video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:Racing video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n\n{{vg-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Angeldeb82", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercar_Street_Challenge"}
