{"title_page": "Lauren Molina", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = \n| image         = LAUREN MOLINA BROADWAY.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Molina on Broadway\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1981|04|15}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Lauren Molina''' (born April 15, 1981) is an American actress, singer, songwriter, and musician. She is a co-creator and performer with the comedy-pop, undie-rock band [[The Skivvies]]. Her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] credits include Johanna in the actor-musician [[revival (theatre)|revival]] of ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'',.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theater.nytimes.com/2005/11/04/theater/reviews/04swee.html?_r=1&oref=login|title=Grand Guignol, Spare and Stark|author=Ben Brantley (theater.nytimes.com)|accessdate=August 6, 2016 }}</ref> To describe her as an actress, one reviewer said \"She's part Mary Martin, Lucille Ball, Kristen Wiig and [fill in the blank with your favorite opera star because Molina has one of the most powerful and flexible voices in the annals of Broadway].\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ofa.fas.harvard.edu/blog/candides-lauren-molina-best-all-possible-worlds|title=Candide's Lauren Molina: The best of all possible worlds|author=Alicia Anstead (ofs.fas.harvard.edu)|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\nWhile performing on the first national tour of Sweeney Todd, she received the Independent Reviewers of New England (IRNE) Award for Best Supporting Actress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nonesuch.com/journal/sweeney-todd-touring-company-wins-five-independent-reviewers-awards|title=Sweeney Todd Touring Company Wins Five Independent Awards|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> She won a Helen Hayes award for her portrayal of Cunegunde in Candide (2010-2011),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/dcs-helen-hayes-winners-include-candide-the-liar-clybourne-park-oklahoma-thurgood-com-178573|title=DC's Helen Hayes Winners Include Candide, The Liar, Clybourne Park, Oklahoma!, Thurgood|author=Kenneth Jones|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> directed by Mary Zimmerman at the Shakespeare Theatre in DC, and received an IRNE nomination for the same role at the Huntington Theatre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huntingtontheatre.org/artists/lauren-molina/|title=Lauren Molina|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> She originated the role of Bella Rose in Desperate Measures (2017-2018) Off-Broadway and received nominations for the Lucille Lortel Award for Outstanding Actress in a Musical <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lortelaward.com/2018|title=2018 Nominees and Recipients|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> and Outer Critics Circle for Best Supporting Actress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://outercritics.org/68th-annual-awards-outer-critics-circle-announce-2017-18-award-winners-harry-potter-and-the-cursed-child-tops-win-list-with-6-awards/|title=68th Annual Awards Outer Critics Circle|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, she and her Skivvies partner Nick Cearley co-conceived a new actor-musician revival of \"You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown\", also playing Lucy and Linus, at the Cincinnati Playhouse in the Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cincyplay.com/archive/you-re-a-good-man-charlie-brown|title=You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\nA [[Detroit]] native, Lauren received her BFA from the [[University of Michigan]] in musical theatre. She resides in [[New York City]].\n\n== Stage career ==\nShe made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut as Johanna in the 2005 [[revival (theatre)|revival]] of ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theater.nytimes.com/2005/11/04/theater/reviews/04swee.html?_r=1&oref=login|title=Grand Guignol, Spare and Stark|author=Ben Brantley (theater.nytimes.com)|accessdate=August 6, 2016 }}</ref> Described as a \"sweet-voiced soprano who...plays the cello beautifully\" by ''[[The New York Times]]'', she received the Independent Reviewers of New England Award Best Supporting Actress, while performing on the first national tour, and was named as one of the \"30 Under 30\" featured on Broadwayspace.com.\n\n[[Hilton Als]], featured Molina in the \"Critic's Notebook\" of [[The New Yorker]], saying \"Most of the kudos for the current revival of Stephen Sondheim\u2019s 1979 musical, \u201cSweeney Todd,\u201d have gone to Patti LuPone and Michael Cerveris. But Lauren Molina also deserves her share. Making her Broadway d\u00e9but as Johanna, Sweeney's long-lost daughter, Molina projects such sweet confusion, mental terror, and consistent interiority that she exposes the ways in which seasoned pros like LuPone and Cerveris play to the audience from time to time. Molina is a newcomer\u2014she only recently graduated from college\u2014but she taps into Johanna with an all-consuming honesty and range. Given her unconventional good looks and delicacy of frame, filmmakers in the sixties and seventies like Lumet, Coppola, and others would have snatched Molina up as quickly as they did the late, great Elizabeth Hartman, who conveyed an effect similar to Molina's in \u201cThe Group,\u201d \u201cYou\u2019re a Big Boy Now,\u201d and \u201cThe Beguiled\u201d \u2014that of a highly intelligent actress in love with being someone other than herself.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2005/12/05/a-cut-above-2|title=A Cut Above|author=Hilton Als|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, she originated the role of Regina/Candi in the 80's rock musical ''[[Rock of Ages (musical)|Rock of Ages]]'' off-Broadway at New World Stages. She played the same role on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] from April 2009 \u2013 August 2010. She won a Helen Hayes Award for the role of [[Cunegonde]] in [[Candide]] in a 2010\u201311 production that was newly adapted and directed by [[Mary Zimmerman]] at the Goodman Theatre, [[Chicago]], the Shakespeare Theatre, [[Washington D.C.]], and The Huntington Theatre in [[Boston]].\n\nShe was also a part of the Drama League Nominated, two person revival of [[Stephen Sondheim]]'s ''[[Marry Me A Little (musical)|Marry Me A Little]]'' with Jason Tam, off-Broadway at the Clurman Theatre with Keen Company. The cast album was recorded by Ghostlight/Sh-K-Boom and released November 2013.\n\nIn 2017, Lauren originated the role of Bella Rose in the Drama Desk Award-Winning Off-Broadway show [[Desperate Measures (musical)|Desperate Measures]]. She received the Lucille Lortel Award for Outstanding Actress in a Musical and Outer Critics Circle for Best Supporting Actress nominations. \nBroadway world said, \"...Lauren Molina, as Bella, gives one of those uproarious performances that used to make people stay home on Saturday nights to see on \"The Carol Burnett Show.\" She mugs unmercifully, belts out a sassy strip number and, [has an] homage to Groucho and Harpo's classic mirror scene in \"Duck Soup.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/BWW-Review-Problem-Solved-Wild-West-Shakespeare-Musical-DESPERATE-MEASURES-is-Hilarious-and-Tuneful-20180622|title=BWW Review: Problem Solved! Wild West Shakespeare Musical DESPERATE MEASURES is Hilarious and Tuneful|author=Michael Dale|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe show began at the [[York Theatre]] then transferred to [[New World Stages]]. She recorded the original cast album released by [[Sony Masterworks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sonymusic.com/masterworks/desperate-measures-original-cast-recording-digital-album-available-today-from-masterworks-broadway/|title=Desperate Measures Original Cast Recording Digital Album Available Today From Masterworks Broadway|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe is a co-conceiver of the new actor-musician revisal of \u201c[[You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown]]\u201d which debuted at the Cincinnati Playhouse in April 2019. She also played the role of Lucy and was described by the Cincinnati Enquirer as \"a powerhouse of a performer\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/entertainment/theater/2019/04/26/review-charlie-brown-playhouse-park/3590856002/|title=Charlie Brown at the playhouse is sweet for kids, sharp for adults|author=David Lyman|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> Critics raved that \u201cThe production at Cincinnati Playhouse in the Park may be the best we are likely to ever encounter, thanks to the inventiveness of the presentation and the talented cast.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.talkinbroadway.com/page/regional/cincy/cincy386.html|title=Regional Reviews: Cincinnati|author=Scott Cain|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe has been seen regionally as Squeaky Fromme in [[Assassins (musical)|Assassins]] directed by [[James Bundy]] (Yale Rep), Eileen in [[Wonderful Town]] directed by [[Mary Zimmerman]] ([[Goodman Theatre]]), Countess in [[A Little Night Music]] directed by [[Peter DuBois]] ([[Huntington Theatre Company]]), Audrey in [[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]] directed by [[Amanda Dehnert]] ([[Cleveland Play House]]), Janet in [[The Rocky Horror Show]] directed by [[Hunter Foster]] ([[Bucks County Playhouse]]), The World Premiere of Meet Me In Saint Louis: A Radio Play directed by Gordon Greenberg (Bucks County Playhouse) and It's a Wonderful Life: A Radio Play directed by Gordon Greenberg (Bucks County Playhouse).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thewriteteachers.com/lauren-molina-joins-the-cast-of-women-of-the-wings-a-celebration-of-female-musical-theatre-writers-volume-ii/|title=Lauren Molina joins the cast of WOMEN OF THE WINGS: A CELEBRATION OF FEMALE MUSICAL THEATRE WRITERS VOLUME II|author=Megan Minutillo|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOther roles she's originated include: Megan in the world premiere musical, ''NOBODY LOVES YOU'', at both [[The Old Globe]] and off-Broadway at Second Stage in 2013; Miss Jones 1 in ''TEN CENTS A DANCE'', with [[Donna McKechnie]] and Malcolm Gets at the Williamstown Theatre Festival (This original musical, created by John Doyle, utilized actor/singer/musicians, Lauren playing cello, bass, guitar, ukulele and saxophone, and expressed the story thru the music of Rodgers and Hart); Liza in ''THE FORTRESS OF SOLITUDE'' by Itamar Moses and Michael Friedman.\n\nShe was a featured singer at \"The Ladies Who Sing Sondheim\" concert with [[Barbara Cook]] and [[Patti Lupone]] at the Westport Playhouse. She also was a soloist at the \"Tribute for [[Angela Lansbury]]\" with Tyne Daly and Christine Ebersole held at the Bucks County Playhouse. In addition, she was a back-up singer for [[Sarah Brightman]] on her La Luna tour.\n\n==Music==\nMolina's vocal diversity ranges from pop belting to [[coloratura soprano]]. She can often be found singing in New York City and across the country with her wit-rock comedy-pop duo [[The Skivvies]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2013/06/23/the-bare-essentials-2|title=The bare essentials|author=Barbara Hoffman (nypost.com)|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref> Lauren and her Skivvies bandmate, [[Nick Cearley]], played Brad and Janet in ''[[The Rocky Horror Show]]'' at the Bucks County Playhouse directed by Hunter Foster in 2013.\n\nIn 2007, Molina released her first EP entitled \"Doo-Be-Doo\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/laurenmolina|title=Doo- Be - Doo|author=Lauren Molina (cdbaby.com)|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref> Featuring all original folk/pop songs, this album is quirky and playful, with instrumentations such as ukulele, cello, guitar, piano, and accordion. In 2010, she released \"Sea For Two\" her first full-length album through the indy label [[Mother West]].\n\nMolina has been a frequent collaborator with [[Jason Reischel]], the Singer-Songwriter behind \"My Cousin, The Emperor\".  In 2007, she played [[cello]] on the song \"Pieces Fall in Place\" for Reischel's solo album ''Irony-Free Parlor Music.''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jasonreischel.bandcamp.com/album/irony-free-parlor-music |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222015423/https://jasonreischel.bandcamp.com/album/irony-free-parlor-music |archivedate=February 22, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Molina also appeared on the My Cousin, The Emperor songs ''Annie (The Levee Song)'' (cello) and ''Somedays'' (cello/vocals) from their 2011 EP ''The Subway Eps, Vol. I: Prospect Park West''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jasonreischel.bandcamp.com/album/the-subway-eps-vol-i-prospect-park-west |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222014742/http://jasonreischel.bandcamp.com/album/the-subway-eps-vol-i-prospect-park-west |archivedate=February 22, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nVideos from live performances can be found on her [https://www.youtube.com/lomo212 youtube channel.]\n\n==Comedy==\nMolina created a webseries entitled \"Rock of Ages Productions\" along with former ''Rock of Ages'' castmates Mitchell Jarvis and Wesley Taylor. This absurd backstage [[mocumentary]] has 17 episodes and can be watched on YouTube at [https://www.youtube.com/rockofagesprod www.youtube.com/rockofagesprod].\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|http://www.laurenmolina.com}}\n* [http://broadwayworld.com/people/Lauren_Molina/ Broadwayworld.com Profile]\n* {{IMDb name|3804428}}\n* [http://www.theskivviesnyc.com The Skivvies Official Website]\n* [[The Skivvies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* Jones, Kenneth. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100918221915/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/143125-Lauren-Molina-and-Geoff-Packard-Are-Optimists-of-Goodman-Candide-Beginning-Sept-17 Lauren Molina and Geoff Packard are Optimists of Goodman Candide]. playbill.com September 17, 2010\n* Brantley, Ben. [http://theater.nytimes.com/2005/11/04/theater/reviews/04swee.html?_r=1&oref=login Grand Guignol, Spare and Stark]. nytimes.com November 4, 2005\n* http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/laurenmolina cdbaby.com\n* Isherwood, Charles. [http://theater.nytimes.com/2009/04/08/theater/reviews/08rock.html Big-Hair Rockers Return in a New Arena:Broadway] April 8, 2009\n* Hetrick, Adam. [https://web.archive.org/web/20131113085814/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/153170-Geoff-Packard-and-Lauren-Molina-Will-Return-to-Candide-at-the-Huntington] July 29, 2011\n* Teachout, Terry. [https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10000872396390443635404578036282352588890] October 4, 2011\n* Hoffman, Barbara. [https://nypost.com/2013/06/23/the-bare-essentials-2/] June 13, 2013\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Molina, Lauren}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from New York City]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan School of Music, Theatre & Dance alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = \n| image         = LAUREN MOLINA BROADWAY.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Molina on Broadway\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1981|04|15}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Lauren Molina''' (born April 15, 1981) is an American actress, singer, songwriter, and musician. She is a co-creator and performer with the comedy-pop, undie-rock band [[The Skivvies]]. Her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] credits include Johanna in the actor-musician [[revival (theatre)|revival]] of ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'',.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theater.nytimes.com/2005/11/04/theater/reviews/04swee.html?_r=1&oref=login|title=Grand Guignol, Spare and Stark|author=Ben Brantley (theater.nytimes.com)|accessdate=August 6, 2016 }}</ref> To describe her as an actress, one reviewer said \"She's part Mary Martin, Lucille Ball, Kristen Wiig and [fill in the blank with your favorite opera star because Molina has one of the most powerful and flexible voices in the annals of Broadway].\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ofa.fas.harvard.edu/blog/candides-lauren-molina-best-all-possible-worlds|title=Candide's Lauren Molina: The best of all possible worlds|author=Alicia Anstead (ofs.fas.harvard.edu)|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\nWhile performing on the first national tour of Sweeney Todd, she received the Independent Reviewers of New England (IRNE) Award for Best Supporting Actress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nonesuch.com/journal/sweeney-todd-touring-company-wins-five-independent-reviewers-awards|title=Sweeney Todd Touring Company Wins Five Independent Awards|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> She won a Helen Hayes award for her portrayal of Cunegunde in Candide (2010-2011),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/dcs-helen-hayes-winners-include-candide-the-liar-clybourne-park-oklahoma-thurgood-com-178573|title=DC's Helen Hayes Winners Include Candide, The Liar, Clybourne Park, Oklahoma!, Thurgood|author=Kenneth Jones|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> directed by Mary Zimmerman at the Shakespeare Theatre in DC, and received an IRNE nomination for the same role at the Huntington Theatre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huntingtontheatre.org/artists/lauren-molina/|title=Lauren Molina|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> She originated the role of Bella Rose in Desperate Measures (2017-2018) Off-Broadway and received nominations for the Lucille Lortel Award for Outstanding Actress in a Musical <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lortelaward.com/2018|title=2018 Nominees and Recipients|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> and Outer Critics Circle for Best Supporting Actress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://outercritics.org/68th-annual-awards-outer-critics-circle-announce-2017-18-award-winners-harry-potter-and-the-cursed-child-tops-win-list-with-6-awards/|title=68th Annual Awards Outer Critics Circle|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, she and her Skivvies partner Nick Cearley co-conceived a new actor-musician revival of \"You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown\", also playing Lucy and Linus, at the Cincinnati Playhouse in the Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cincyplay.com/archive/you-re-a-good-man-charlie-brown|title=You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\nA [[Detroit]] native, Lauren received her BFA from the [[University of Michigan]] in musical theatre. She resides in [[New York City]].\n\n== Stage career ==\nShe made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut as Johanna in the 2005 [[revival (theatre)|revival]] of ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theater.nytimes.com/2005/11/04/theater/reviews/04swee.html?_r=1&oref=login|title=Grand Guignol, Spare and Stark|author=Ben Brantley (theater.nytimes.com)|accessdate=August 6, 2016 }}</ref> Described as a \"sweet-voiced soprano who...plays the cello beautifully\" by ''[[The New York Times]]'', she received the Independent Reviewers of New England Award Best Supporting Actress, while performing on the first national tour, and was named as one of the \"30 Under 30\" featured on Broadwayspace.com.\n\n[[Hilton Als]], featured Molina in the \"Critic's Notebook\" of [[The New Yorker]], saying \"Most of the kudos for the current revival of Stephen Sondheim\u2019s 1979 musical, \u201cSweeney Todd,\u201d have gone to Patti LuPone and Michael Cerveris. But Lauren Molina also deserves her share. Making her Broadway d\u00e9but as Johanna, Sweeney's long-lost daughter, Molina projects such sweet confusion, mental terror, and consistent interiority that she exposes the ways in which seasoned pros like LuPone and Cerveris play to the audience from time to time. Molina is a newcomer\u2014she only recently graduated from college\u2014but she taps into Johanna with an all-consuming honesty and range. Given her unconventional good looks and delicacy of frame, filmmakers in the sixties and seventies like Lumet, Coppola, and others would have snatched Molina up as quickly as they did the late, great Elizabeth Hartman, who conveyed an effect similar to Molina's in \u201cThe Group,\u201d \u201cYou\u2019re a Big Boy Now,\u201d and \u201cThe Beguiled\u201d \u2014that of a highly intelligent actress in love with being someone other than herself.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2005/12/05/a-cut-above-2|title=A Cut Above|author=Hilton Als|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, she originated the role of Regina/Candi in the 80's rock musical ''[[Rock of Ages (musical)|Rock of Ages]]'' off-Broadway at New World Stages. She played the same role on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] from April 2009 \u2013 August 2010. She won a Helen Hayes Award for the role of [[Cunegonde]] in [[Candide]] in a 2010\u201311 production that was newly adapted and directed by [[Mary Zimmerman]] at the Goodman Theatre, [[Chicago]], the Shakespeare Theatre, [[Washington D.C.]], and The Huntington Theatre in [[Boston]].\n\nShe was also a part of the Drama League Nominated, two person revival of [[Stephen Sondheim]]'s ''[[Marry Me A Little (musical)|Marry Me A Little]]'' with Jason Tam, off-Broadway at the Clurman Theatre with Keen Company. The cast album was recorded by Ghostlight/Sh-K-Boom and released November 2013.\n\nIn 2017, Lauren originated the role of Bella Rose in the Drama Desk Award-Winning Off-Broadway show [[Desperate Measures (musical)|Desperate Measures]]. She received the Lucille Lortel Award for Outstanding Actress in a Musical and Outer Critics Circle for Best Supporting Actress nominations. \nBroadway world said, \"...Lauren Molina, as Bella, gives one of those uproarious performances that used to make people stay home on Saturday nights to see on \"The Carol Burnett Show.\" She mugs unmercifully, belts out a sassy strip number and, [has an] homage to Groucho and Harpo's classic mirror scene in \"Duck Soup.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/BWW-Review-Problem-Solved-Wild-West-Shakespeare-Musical-DESPERATE-MEASURES-is-Hilarious-and-Tuneful-20180622|title=BWW Review: Problem Solved! WIld West Shakespeare Musical DESPERATE MEASURES is Hilarious and Tuneful|author=Michael Dale|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe show began at the [[York Theatre]] then transferred to [[New World Stages]]. She recorded the original cast album released by [[Sony Masterworks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sonymusic.com/masterworks/desperate-measures-original-cast-recording-digital-album-available-today-from-masterworks-broadway/|title=Desperate Measures Original Cast Recording Digital Album Available Today From Masterworks Broadway|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe is a co-conceiver of the new actor-musician revisal of \u201c[[You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown]]\u201d which debuted at the Cincinnati Playhouse in April 2019. She also played the role of Lucy and was described by the Cincinnati Enquirer as \"a powerhouse of a performer\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/entertainment/theater/2019/04/26/review-charlie-brown-playhouse-park/3590856002/|title=Charlie Brown at the playhouse is sweet for kids, sharp for adults|author=David Lyman|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> Critics raved that \u201cThe production at Cincinnati Playhouse in the Park may be the best we are likely to ever encounter, thanks to the inventiveness of the presentation and the talented cast.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.talkinbroadway.com/page/regional/cincy/cincy386.html|title=Regional Reviews: Cincinnati|author=Scott Cain|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe has been seen regionally as Squeaky Fromme in [[Assassins (musical)|Assassins]] directed by [[James Bundy]] (Yale Rep), Eileen in [[Wonderful Town]] directed by [[Mary Zimmerman]] ([[Goodman Theatre]]), Countess in [[A Little Night Music]] directed by [[Peter DuBois]] ([[Huntington Theatre Company]]), Audrey in [[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]] directed by [[Amanda Dehnert]] ([[Cleveland Play House]]), Janet in [[The Rocky Horror Show]] directed by [[Hunter Foster]] ([[Bucks County Playhouse]]), The World Premiere of Meet Me In Saint Louis: A Radio Play directed by Gordon Greenberg (Bucks County Playhouse) and It's a Wonderful Life: A Radio Play directed by Gordon Greenberg (Bucks County Playhouse).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thewriteteachers.com/lauren-molina-joins-the-cast-of-women-of-the-wings-a-celebration-of-female-musical-theatre-writers-volume-ii/|title=Lauren Molina joins the cast of WOMEN OF THE WINGS: A CELEBRATION OF FEMALE MUSICAL THEATRE WRITERS VOLUME II|author=Megan Minutillo|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOther roles she's originated include: Megan in the world premiere musical, ''NOBODY LOVES YOU'', at both [[The Old Globe]] and off-Broadway at Second Stage in 2013; Miss Jones 1 in ''TEN CENTS A DANCE'', with [[Donna McKechnie]] and Malcolm Gets at the Williamstown Theatre Festival (This original musical, created by John Doyle, utilized actor/singer/musicians, Lauren playing cello, bass, guitar, ukulele and saxophone, and expressed the story thru the music of Rodgers and Hart); Liza in ''THE FORTRESS OF SOLITUDE'' by Itamar Moses and Michael Friedman.\n\nShe was a featured singer at \"The Ladies Who Sing Sondheim\" concert with [[Barbara Cook]] and [[Patti Lupone]] at the Westport Playhouse. She also was a soloist at the \"Tribute for [[Angela Lansbury]]\" with Tyne Daly and Christine Ebersole held at the Bucks County Playhouse. In addition, she was a back-up singer for [[Sarah Brightman]] on her La Luna tour.\n\n==Music==\nMolina's vocal diversity ranges from pop belting to [[coloratura soprano]]. She can often be found singing in New York City and across the country with her wit-rock comedy-pop duo [[The Skivvies]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2013/06/23/the-bare-essentials-2|title=The bare essentials|author=Barbara Hoffman (nypost.com)|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref> Lauren and her Skivvies bandmate, [[Nick Cearley]], played Brad and Janet in ''[[The Rocky Horror Show]]'' at the Bucks County Playhouse directed by Hunter Foster in 2013.\n\nIn 2007, Molina released her first EP entitled \"Doo-Be-Doo\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/laurenmolina|title=Doo- Be - Doo|author=Lauren Molina (cdbaby.com)|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref> Featuring all original folk/pop songs, this album is quirky and playful, with instrumentations such as ukulele, cello, guitar, piano, and accordion. In 2010, she released \"Sea For Two\" her first full-length album through the indy label [[Mother West]].\n\nMolina has been a frequent collaborator with [[Jason Reischel]], the Singer-Songwriter behind \"My Cousin, The Emperor\".  In 2007, she played [[cello]] on the song \"Pieces Fall in Place\" for Reischel's solo album ''Irony-Free Parlor Music.''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jasonreischel.bandcamp.com/album/irony-free-parlor-music |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222015423/https://jasonreischel.bandcamp.com/album/irony-free-parlor-music |archivedate=February 22, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Molina also appeared on the My Cousin, The Emperor songs ''Annie (The Levee Song)'' (cello) and ''Somedays'' (cello/vocals) from their 2011 EP ''The Subway Eps, Vol. I: Prospect Park West''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jasonreischel.bandcamp.com/album/the-subway-eps-vol-i-prospect-park-west |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222014742/http://jasonreischel.bandcamp.com/album/the-subway-eps-vol-i-prospect-park-west |archivedate=February 22, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nVideos from live performances can be found on her [https://www.youtube.com/lomo212 youtube channel.]\n\n==Comedy==\nMolina created a webseries entitled \"Rock of Ages Productions\" along with former ''Rock of Ages'' castmates Mitchell Jarvis and Wesley Taylor. This absurd backstage [[mocumentary]] has 17 episodes and can be watched on YouTube at [https://www.youtube.com/rockofagesprod www.youtube.com/rockofagesprod].\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|http://www.laurenmolina.com}}\n* [http://broadwayworld.com/people/Lauren_Molina/ Broadwayworld.com Profile]\n* {{IMDb name|3804428}}\n* [http://www.theskivviesnyc.com The Skivvies Official Website]\n* [[The Skivvies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* Jones, Kenneth. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100918221915/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/143125-Lauren-Molina-and-Geoff-Packard-Are-Optimists-of-Goodman-Candide-Beginning-Sept-17 Lauren Molina and Geoff Packard are Optimists of Goodman Candide]. playbill.com September 17, 2010\n* Brantley, Ben. [http://theater.nytimes.com/2005/11/04/theater/reviews/04swee.html?_r=1&oref=login Grand Guignol, Spare and Stark]. nytimes.com November 4, 2005\n* http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/laurenmolina cdbaby.com\n* Isherwood, Charles. [http://theater.nytimes.com/2009/04/08/theater/reviews/08rock.html Big-Hair Rockers Return in a New Arena:Broadway] April 8, 2009\n* Hetrick, Adam. [https://web.archive.org/web/20131113085814/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/153170-Geoff-Packard-and-Lauren-Molina-Will-Return-to-Candide-at-the-Huntington] July 29, 2011\n* Teachout, Terry. [https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10000872396390443635404578036282352588890] October 4, 2011\n* Hoffman, Barbara. [https://nypost.com/2013/06/23/the-bare-essentials-2/] June 13, 2013\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Molina, Lauren}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from New York City]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan School of Music, Theatre & Dance alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauren_Molina"}
{"title_page": "Apolo Ohno", "text_new": "{{short description|American short track speed skater}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox speed skater\n| sport       = [[Short track speed skating]]\n| name        = Apolo Ohno\n| image       = ApoloOhno.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Ohno at the [[2006 Winter Olympics]] in [[Turin]]\n| alt = A man wearing a gold medal smiles with his arms raised above his head holding a flower bouquet in his left hand while wearing a dark blue tracksuit and a red bandanna on his head. There is a portion of the ice-rink in the background.\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1982|5|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Athletes {{ndash}} Apolo Anton Ohno|website=U.S. Speedskating|url=http://www.usspeedskating.org/athlete/apolo-anton-ohno |accessdate=January 13, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114174238/http://www.usspeedskating.org/athlete/apolo-anton-ohno|archivedate=January 14, 2014}}</ref>\n| height      = 5 ft 8 in<ref>{{cite web|title=Apolo Ohno|url=http://www.teamusa.org/us-speedskating/athletes/Apolo-Ohno|website=teamusa.org|publisher=[[United States Olympic Committee]]|accessdate=January 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202080126/http://www.teamusa.org/us-speedskating/athletes/Apolo-Ohno|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| weight      = {{convert|65.7|kg|lb stlb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website     = {{URL|www.apoloohno.com|ApoloOhno.com}}\n| country     = {{flag|United States of America}}\n| pb          = 500&nbsp;m: 41.518 (2003)<ref name=\"personal best\" /><br>1000&nbsp;m: 1:24.500 (2009)<ref name=\"2009 trials\" /><br>1500&nbsp;m: 2:11.280 (2003)<ref name=\"personal best\" /><br>3000&nbsp;m: 4:32.975 (2003)<ref name=\"personal best\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.fwps.org/info/notable/ohno.html |title=Federal Way Public Schools Graduates of Note |accessdate=December 22, 2009 |work=Federal Way Public Schools |publisher=ApoloAntonOhno.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617013409/http://www.fwps.org/info/notable/ohno.html |archivedate=June 17, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| retired     = 2010\n| worlds      = '''World Championship'''<br>[[2008 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2008]] Overall<br>'''World Cup'''<br>2001 Overall<br>2003 Overall<br>2005 Overall\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[short track speed skating]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Winter Olympics|Olympic Games]]|2|2|4\n|[[World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|World Championships]]|8|7|6\n|[[World Short Track Speed Skating Team Championships|World Team Championships]]|1|0|1\n}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[Winter Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2002 Winter Olympics|2002 Salt Lake City]] | [[Short track speed skating at the 2002 Winter Olympics|1500&nbsp;m]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2006 Winter Olympics|2006 Turin]] |[[Short track speed skating at the 2006 Winter Olympics#Men's events|500&nbsp;m]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2002 Winter Olympics|2002 Salt Lake City]] | [[Short track speed skating at the 2002 Winter Olympics|1000&nbsp;m]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Vancouver]] | [[Short track speed skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 1500 metres|1500&nbsp;m]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2006 Turin |[[Short track speed skating at the 2006 Winter Olympics#Men's events|1000&nbsp;m]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2006 Turin |[[Short track speed skating at the 2006 Winter Olympics#Men's events|5000&nbsp;m relay]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2010 Vancouver | [[Short track speed skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 1000 metres|1000&nbsp;m]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2010 Vancouver | [[Short track speed skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 5000 metre relay|5000&nbsp;m relay]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2001 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2001 Jeonju]] | 1500&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalGold| 2001 Jeonju | 5000&nbsp;m relay}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2005 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2005 Beijing]] | 1000&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalGold| 2005 Beijing | 3000&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2007 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2007 Milan]] | 1500&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2008 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2008 Gangneung]] | '''Overall'''}}\n{{MedalGold| 2008 Gangneung | 500&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2009 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2009 Vienna]] | 5000&nbsp;m relay}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[1999 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|1999 Sofia]] | 500&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalSilver| 2001 Jeonju | '''Overall'''}}\n{{MedalSilver| 2001 Jeonju | 1000&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2003 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2003 Warsaw]] | 3000&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalSilver| 2005 Beijing | '''Overall'''}}\n{{MedalSilver| 2008 Gangneung | 1000&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalSilver| 2009 Vienna | 1000&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2005 Beijing | 5000&nbsp;m relay}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2007 Milan | '''Overall'''}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2007 Milan | 1000&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2007 Milan | 3000&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2007 Milan | 5000&nbsp;m relay}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2008 Gangneung | 3000&nbsp;m}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[World Short Track Speed Skating Team Championships|World Team Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| 2008 Harbin | Team}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2009 Heerenveen | Team}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[World Junior Short Track Speed Skating Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| 1999 Montreal | '''Overall'''}}\n}}\n\n'''Apolo Anton Ohno''' ({{IPAc-en|\u0259|\u02c8|p|\u0252|l|o\u028a|_|\u02c8|\u00e6|n|t|\u0252|n|_|\u02c8|o\u028a|n|o\u028a}}; born May 22, 1982) is an American retired<ref>{{cite web |title=Ohno rules out Sochi, says career is over |url=https://tv.yahoo.com/news/newly-retired-apolo-ohno-tv-olympics-235850935.html |publisher=AP via Yahoo |accessdate=February 10, 2014 |author=Harris, Beth |date=July 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302013644/http://tv.yahoo.com/news/newly-retired-apolo-ohno-tv-olympics-235850935.html |archive-date=March 2, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[short track speed skating]] competitor and an eight-time medalist (two gold, two silver, four bronze) in the [[Winter Olympics]]. Ohno is the most decorated American Olympian at the Winter Olympics and was inducted into the [[U.S. Olympic Hall of Fame]] in 2019.\n\nRaised by his father, Ohno began training full-time in 1996. He has been the face of short track in the United States since winning his medals at the [[2002 Winter Olympics]].<ref name=\"popular1\"/><ref name=\"hollywood\"/> At the age of 14, he became the youngest U.S. national champion in 1997 and was the reigning champion from 2001\u20132009, winning the title a total of 12 times.<ref name=\"familylife\"/><ref name=\"NBC Olympics\"/> In December 1999, he became the youngest skater to win a World Cup event title, and became the first American to win a [[Short Track Speed Skating World Cup|World Cup overall]] title in 2001, which he won again in 2003 and 2005.<ref name=\"NBC Olympics\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=2173/bio/index.html |title=Apolo Ohno Vancouver Olympics Profile |accessdate=August 13, 2009 |publisher=NBC Olympics |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091110033745/http://www.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=2173/bio/index.html |archive-date=November 10, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Ohno Wins 1,500 Short-Track Title |date=December 19, 1999 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19991219&slug=3002427 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 22, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305184749/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19991219&slug=3002427 |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> He won his first overall World Championship title at the [[2008 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2008 championships]].\n\nOhno's accolades and accomplishments include being the [[United States Olympic Committee]]'s Male Athlete of the Month in October 2003 and March 2008, the U.S. Speedskating's Athlete of the Year for 2003, and was a 2002, 2003 and 2006 finalist for the [[James E. Sullivan Award|Sullivan Award]], which recognizes the best amateur athlete in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news |title=USOC Athletes of the Month \u2013 March 2008 |date=April 18, 2008 |publisher=US Speed Skating |url=http://speedskating.teamusa.org/news/article/356 |accessdate=August 11, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305185932/http://speedskating.teamusa.org/news/article/356 |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=McMurray takes last pole in Winston Cup history |date=November 15, 2003 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20031115&slug=digs15 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 11, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305191431/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20031115&slug=digs15 |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"yahoo profile\">{{Cite news|title=2006 Winter Olympics Athlete Profile \u2013 Apolo Ohno |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/olympics/torino2006/usa/Apolo+Anton+Ohno/607532 |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |accessdate=August 11, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405012548/https://sports.yahoo.com/olympics/torino2006/usa/Apolo%2BAnton%2BOhno/607532 |archivedate=April 5, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=AAU Sullivan Award \u2013 Who is the top amateur athlete? |date=March 6, 2007 |url=http://aaunews.org/news/?p=170 |work=USA Today |accessdate=August 11, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090319024523/http://aaunews.org/news/?p=170 |archive-date=March 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Since gaining recognition through his sport, Ohno has worked as a [[motivational speaker]], [[philanthropist]], started a nutritional supplement business, and in 2007, competed on and won the reality TV show ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''. Ohno later became host of a revival of ''[[Minute to Win It]]'' on [[Game Show Network]] and served as a commentator for [[NBC]]'s coverage of the [[2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Winter Games]] in [[Sochi]] and the [[2018 Winter Olympics|2018 Winter Games]] in [[Pyeongchang]].  Ohno has expressed his entrepreneurial appetite for technology and health and wellness industries.\n\n==Early life==\nOhno was born in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], to a [[Japanese people|Japanese]]-born father, {{Nihongo|Yuki Ohno|\u5927\u91ce \u5e78|''\u014cno Yuki''}} and a European American mother, Jerrie Lee.<ref name=\"decision\">{{Cite news |first=Percy |last=Allen |title=Fed. Way Speedskater Decides To Take His Time |date=March 15, 1996 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19960315&slug=2319087 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 22, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305184743/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19960315&slug=2319087 |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ohno's parents divorced when he was an infant, and he was raised in [[Seattle]] by his father.<ref name=SI/> He has had little contact with his biological mother and as of 2002 had expressed no interest in knowing her or his older half-brother.<ref name=\"decision\"/><ref name=\"SI\">{{cite news|last1=Price|first1=S.L.|title=Launch of Apolo|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/si_online/news/2002/02/13/launch_of_apolo/|accessdate=February 20, 2018|work=[[Sports Illustrated]] (via [[CNN Sports Illustrated#CNN/SI website|cnnsi.com]])|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020726200041/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/si_online/news/2002/02/13/launch_of_apolo/|archivedate=July 26, 2002|quote=He shrugs when asked about the mother who left him when he was a year old; he knows little about her and professes to have no interest in learning more about her.}}</ref><ref name=\"book1315\">Ohno & Richardson 2002, pp. 13\u201315.</ref> Ohno's father, a hair stylist and owner of the salon ''Yuki's Diffusion'', often worked 12-hour shifts, and with no extended family in the United States, found it hard to balance his career with raising a child.<ref name=\"book1315\"/> His father chose to name his son Apolo after the [[Greek language|Greek]] words ''apo'', which means to \"steer away from\" and ''lo'', which means \"look out; here he comes.\"<ref name=\"NBC Olympics\"/>\n\nWhen Ohno was very young, his father meticulously researched [[Day care|childcare]] providers to care for his son during his long work hours.<ref name=\"book1315\"/> As Apolo grew older, his father became concerned his son would become a [[latchkey kid]], so Yuki got his son involved with competitive swimming and quad-speed roller skating at age 6. He later switched from the instruction of Benton Redford, a National Champion, to a team in [[Federal Way, Washington]] called Pattison's Team Extreme and became a national inline speedskating champion and record holder himself. His father used inline speed skating to fill his spare time.<ref name=\"familylife\">{{Cite news |first=Elliot |last=Almond |title=Winter Olympic Profile / Apolo Ohno \u2013 Completing A Family Circle |date=January 15, 1998 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980115&slug=2728777 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 22, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225040428/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980115&slug=2728777 |archive-date=February 25, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ohno's days were spent with morning swimming practices, followed by schooling, and finally skating practices in the afternoon.<ref name=\"book2223\">Ohno & Richardson 2002, pp. 22\u201323.</ref>\n\nWhen Ohno was 12, he won the Washington state championship in the [[breaststroke]], but preferred inline speed skating over swimming.<ref name=\"book2223\"/> He has stated that by the time he turned 13, he attended parties with older teenagers if he did not have competitions on the weekends.<ref>Ohno & Richardson 2002, p. 19.</ref> His father has stated that it was a struggle balancing his son's desire for independence while helping him reach his potential as a young athlete.<ref name=\"familylife\"/>\n\n==Skating career==\n\n===Beginnings===\nWhen he was 13 years old, Ohno became interested in [[short track speed skating]] after seeing the sport during the [[1994 Olympics]] in [[Lillehammer]].<ref name=GMA>{{Cite news |first=Ron |last=Claiborne |title=Apolo Ohno Has a Single Father Behind His Success |date=June 18, 2006 |url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/GMA/ESPNSports/story?id=2090015&page=1 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=April 11, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208115016/http://www.abcnews.go.com/GMA/ESPNSports/story?id=2090015&page=1 |archive-date=December 8, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> His father capitalized on this interest by driving him to short track competitions throughout the northwest United States and Canada, and Ohno won several competitions in his age divisions.<ref name=\"decision\"/><ref name=SI/> His father wanted to encourage Ohno to develop his skills and, although Ohno was underage, he got him admitted to the [[Lake Placid Olympic Training Center]] in 1996 to train full-time for short track.<ref name=\"SI\" /> At 13, Ohno was the youngest skater admitted to the center.<ref name=\"familylife\"/>\n\nAt first, Ohno's commitment at Lake Placid was low until his teammates nicknamed him \"Chunky\", which motivated him to train harder.<ref name=\"decision\"/> In January, he failed to make the 1997 U.S. Junior World Team.<ref>Ohno & Richardson 2002, p. 46.</ref> Ohno adjusted his training and made a comeback winning the 1997 U.S. Senior Championships overall title, taking a gold medal in the 1500&nbsp;m, a silver in the 300&nbsp;m, and came in fourth in the 500&nbsp;m races.<ref name=\"familylife\"/><ref name=\"book\">Ohno & Richardson 2002, pp. 48\u201352.</ref> At the age of 14, he became the youngest person to win the title.<ref name=\"familylife\"/> Ohno then relocated to the [[United States Olympic Training Center|Colorado Springs Olympic Training Center]] to begin training with the senior level skaters, despite being only 14&nbsp;years old.<ref name=\"book\"/>\n\nHowever, Ohno would struggle at the 1997 World Championships in [[Nagano, Nagano|Nagano]], [[Japan]], finishing 19th overall.<ref name=\"book\"/> After this disappointing defeat at his first appearance at a world championships, Ohno returned home to Seattle.<ref name=\"book\"/> He did not train from April to August 1997, so he gained weight and was ill-prepared for the [[1998 Winter Olympics|1998 Nagano Winter Olympics]].<ref name=\"book\"/> As a result, he finished last in the Olympic trials and did not qualify for the Olympic team.<ref name=SI/> Because of his losses at the World Championships and his failure to qualify for the Olympic team, Ohno recommitted himself to the sport and returned to junior-level skating at Lake Placid, rather than at Colorado Springs.<ref name=\"book\"/>\n\nAt the 1999 World Junior Championships, Ohno won first overall, placing first in the 1000&nbsp;m and 1500&nbsp;m, and winning silver in the 500&nbsp;m.<ref name=\"yahoo profile\" /> He won his second senior U.S. national championship in 1999. He finished fourth overall at the [[1999 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|1999 World Championships]] and earned a silver medal in the 500&nbsp;m.<ref name=\"yahoo profile\" /> At the 2000 U.S. Championships, Ohno was unable to defend his title and finished third overall.<ref name=\"yahoo profile\" /> At the [[2000 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2000 World Championships]], Ohno finished ninth overall.<ref name=\"yahoo profile\" /> In the 2000\u20132001 season, Ohno won his first World Cup overall title, regained his National title, and finished second overall in the [[2001 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|World Championships]], losing to Chinese skater [[Li Jiajun]].<ref name=\"yahoo profile\" /><ref>Ohno & Richardson 2002, pp. 91\u201394.</ref>\n\n===2002 Winter Olympics===\n{{See also|Short track speed skating at the 2002 Winter Olympics }}\n\n====Qualification race controversy====\nIn December 2001, during the U.S. Short Track Speed Skating 2002 Olympic Trials, speed skater [[Shani Davis]] was racing for a position on the short track team. Ohno and fellow skater [[Rusty Smith (speed skater)|Rusty Smith]] had already earned slots on the six-man team due to points earned from earlier races. In order for Davis to qualify, he had to place first in the final race\u2014the 1000&nbsp;m\u2014by overcoming stronger skaters Ohno, Smith, and [[Ron Biondo]].<ref name=\"Cazeneuve\">{{Cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/olympics/2002/news/2002/02/13/cazeneuve_ohno/|title=More on the great short-track speed skating controversy|last=Cazeneuve|first=Brian|date=February 13, 2002|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=June 9, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816114944/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/olympics/2002/news/2002/02/13/cazeneuve_ohno/|archive-date=August 16, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Since Ohno had been dominant in the meet to this point by winning every race he entered, a win by Davis seemed to be unlikely.\n\nThough Ohno, Smith, and Biondo were heavily favored to win the 1000&nbsp;m, the race ended with Ohno finishing third, Smith second, and Davis at the top of the podium. Prior to crossing the finish line, Ohno started celebrating for Davis and Smith.<ref name=\"Cazeneuve\" /> Davis' first-place finish earned enough points to move past Tommy O'Hare in the final point standings and to qualify for sixth place. By finishing second, Smith earned the opportunity to skate individually in the 1000&nbsp;m. The victory celebration was short-lived as rumors began that Ohno and Smith, both good friends of Davis, intentionally threw the race so Davis would win.<ref name=SI/>\n\nAfter returning to [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]], O'Hare, who did not skate in the 1000&nbsp;m, filed a formal complaint. The complaint was founded on Ohno's seemingly deliberate attempt to stop Biondo from being able to pass Smith.<ref name=\"complaint\">{{Cite news |first=Selena |last=Roberts |title=OLYMPICS; Fix charge is a threat to skater Ohno |date=January 22, 2002 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/22/sports/olympics-fix-charge-is-a-threat-to-skater-ohno.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=June 9, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012002720/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/22/sports/olympics-fix-charge-is-a-threat-to-skater-ohno.html |archive-date=October 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Because of that blocking move on Biondo, Smith finished in second place and Davis finished first.<ref name=\"complaint\"/> For three days, Ohno, Smith, and Davis stood before an arbitration panel of the United States Olympic Committee.<ref name=\"Cazeneuve\" /> During the hearing, Davis was never accused of being at fault and Smith made the statement: \"Any allegation that there was a fix, conspiracy, or understanding between Apolo and me, or anyone else, to let Shani win the race is completely false. Shani is a great athlete, skated a great race, and deserves to be on the team.\"<ref name=\"complaint\"/> The final verdict was that O'Hare's claims went unproven, all three were absolved of guilt, and the claim was dismissed.<ref name=\"dismissed\">{{Cite news |first=Ron |last=Judd |title=Ohno cleared of fixing U.S. trials |date=January 25, 2002 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20020125&slug=ohno25 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=June 9, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305185907/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20020125&slug=ohno25 |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the dismissal, Ohno stated, \"I am thrilled that the arbitration process has officially vindicated me... As I've said since the moment of these accusations, they were untrue and I did nothing wrong\".<ref name=\"dismissed\" />\n\n====Games====\n[[File:Apolo Ohno's speed skates.jpg|right|thumbnail|alt=Metallic silver skates with golden blades in a glass case with the right skate being slightly elevated.  There is a burgundy curtain behind the skates.  The blades are much longer than the actual boot of the skates.|The skates Ohno wore at the 2002 Winter Olympics are preserved in the [[Smithsonian Institution]] [[National Museum of American History]].]] At the [[2002 Winter Olympics]] in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]], Ohno emerged as the face of short-track speed skating among American fans.<ref name=\"more\">{{Cite news |first=Jim |last=Caple |title=Apolo's great name sucked us into short track |date=February 23, 2002 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/winter02/speed/story?id=1339797 |publisher=ESPN.com |accessdate=August 24, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209111156/http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/winter02/speed/story?id=1339797 |archive-date=December 9, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was a medalist in two events but there was controversy associated with the results.\n\nAfter a disqualification in the 500&nbsp;m race,<ref name=\"disqualified\">{{Cite news |title=Ohno disqualified in 500, U.S. falls in 5,000 relay |date=February 23, 2002 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/winter02/speed/news?id=1339742 |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=February 16, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060301220624/http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/winter02/speed/news?id=1339742 |archive-date=March 1, 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref> he was leading the skaters in the 1000&nbsp;m race. During a turn around the final corner, Ohno, [[Ahn Hyun Soo]], [[Li Jiajun]], and [[Mathieu Turcotte]] all fell in a series of collisions.<ref name=\"collision1\">{{Cite news |title=South Koreans hold Ohno to bronze in 1,000 meter short track |date=February 18, 2006 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20060218&slug=webohno18 |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=February 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926175651/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20060218&slug=webohno18 |archive-date=September 26, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"collision2\">{{Cite news |title=Ohno takes silver after being tripped at short-track finish |date=February 17, 2002 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/olympics/2002/speed_skating/news/2002/02/16/short_track_ap/ |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=February 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100219032945/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/olympics/2002/speed_skating/news/2002/02/16/short_track_ap/ |archive-date=February 19, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The last man standing was [[Steven Bradbury (speed skater)|Steven Bradbury]] from [[Australia]], who was trailing behind at the time, and skated through to win the gold medal, becoming the first person from the southern hemisphere to win a gold medal at a Winter Olympics.<ref>Gordon (2003), pp. 287.</ref> Ohno quickly got to his feet and crossed the finish line to win silver with Turcotte winning the bronze.<ref name=\"more\"/> Ohno, coincidentally, was wearing skates made by Bradbury's own boot company, Revolutionary Boot Company. Bradbury had given them to Ohno, expecting for Ohno to win wearing them.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/feb/18/olympicgames.winterolympics2002 |title=Archived copy |access-date=December 13, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217070153/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/feb/18/olympicgames.winterolympics2002 |archive-date=February 17, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1500&nbsp;m final race, with one lap remaining and currently in second place, Ohno attempted to make a pass on the leader [[Kim Dong-Sung]], who then drifted to the inside and as a result, Ohno raised his arms to signal he was blocked. Kim finished first ahead of Ohno but was disqualified for impeding, awarding the gold medal to Ohno. Fourth-place finisher of the race, [[Fabio Carta]] of Italy, showed his disagreement with the disqualification decision saying it was \"absurd that the Korean was disqualified\".<ref name=\"stptimes\"/> China's Jiajun Li, who moved from bronze to silver, remained neutral saying: \"I respect the decision of the referee, I'm not going to say any more\".<ref name=\"stptimes\"/> [[Steven Bradbury (speed skater)|Steven Bradbury]], the 1000&nbsp;m gold-medal winner, also shared his views: \"Whether Dong-Sung moved across enough to be called for cross-tracking, I don't know, he obviously moved across a bit. It's the judge's interpretation. A lot of people will say it was right and a lot of people will say it's wrong. I've seen moves like that before that were not called. But I've seen them called too\".<ref name=\"stptimes\">{{Cite news|title=Ohno finishes second, then first as winner is disqualified |date=August 24, 2002 |work=St. Petersburg Times |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2002/02/21/Olympics/Ohno_finishes_second_.shtml |accessdate=March 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208161638/http://www.sptimes.com/2002/02/21/Olympics/Ohno_finishes_second_.shtml |archivedate=December 8, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"protestDQ\">{{Cite news |title=South Korean DQ'd; officials promise protest |date=February 23, 2002 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/winter02/speed/news?id=1337596 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=March 14, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210232707/http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/winter02/speed/news?id=1337596 |archive-date=December 10, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Apolo Ohno, 2002.jpg|right|thumbnail|alt=A black and white photo featuring a joyous man with a large smile who is giving an interview to a group of smiling news reporters that are crowded around him.|Ohno in Seattle, Washington, shortly after the 2002 Winter Olympics.]]\nThe South Korean team immediately protested the decision of the chief official of the race, but their protests were denied by the [[International Skating Union|International Skating Union (ISU)]].<ref name=\"disqualified\"/><ref name=\"protestDQ\"/><ref name=\"sportslaw2002\">Epstein (2002), 272\u2013273.</ref> The Korean team then appealed to the [[International Olympic Committee|International Olympic Committee (IOC)]] and the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport|Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS)]].<ref name=\"disqualified\"/><ref name=\"sportslaw2002\"/> The IOC refused to see the case, stating, \"This is a matter for the ISU to decide on. At this time, the IOC has received no proposal and taken no action\".<ref name=\"disqualified\"/> The CAS sided with the officials of the race as \"there is no provision in the short-track rule book for overturning a judgment call by the referee\" after the Korean team asked to have a video replay be used to determine whether or not there was a rule violation.<ref name=\"disqualified\"/><ref name=\"sportslaw2002\"/>\n\nThe disqualification upset South Korean supporters, many of whom directed their anger at Ohno and the [[International Olympic Committee]]. A large number of e-mails protesting the race results crashed the Olympic Committee's email server, and thousands of accusatory letters, many of which contained death threats, were sent to Ohno and the committee.<ref name=\"disqualified\"/><ref>{{Cite news |title=Skating union rejects protest of South Korean's DQ |date=February 21, 2002 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/olympics/2002/speed_skating/news/2002/02/21/south_korea_lawsuit_ap/ |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=February 16, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061029051444/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/olympics/2002/speed_skating/news/2002/02/21/south_korea_lawsuit_ap/ |archive-date=October 29, 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=\uc2dc\uc5f0 |last=\uae40 |script-title=ko:'\ube7c\uc557\uae34 \uae08\uba54\ub2ec', \uacbd\uae30\ub294 \ub05d\ub0ac\uc9c0\ub9cc... |date=February 21, 2002 |url=http://www.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?at_code=67126 |work=Yonhap News, Oh my News |accessdate=February 25, 2007 |language=Korean |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015040411/http://ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?at_code=67126 |archivedate=October 15, 2007 }}</ref> Ohno shared his thoughts on the Koreans' hostile reaction by saying, \"I was really bothered by it. I grew up around many Asian cultures, Korean one of them. A lot of my best friends were Korean growing up. I just didn't understand. Later on I realized that was built up by certain people and that was directed at me, negative energy from other things, not even resulting around the sport, but around politics, using me to stand on the pedestal as the anti-American sentiment\".<ref>{{Cite news |first=Eric |last=Gold |title=Speedskating's Apolo Anton Ohno |publisher=The Sports Network |url=http://theseoultimes.com/ST/?url=/ST/db/read.php?idx=2936 |work=The Seoul Times |accessdate=August 13, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060323121933/http://theseoultimes.com/ST/?url=%2FST%2Fdb%2Fread.php%3Fidx%3D2936 |archive-date=March 23, 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first=Karen |last=Crouse |title=Ohno Is hoping for victories and thaw in icy relations with South Koreans |date=February 16, 2006 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE3DE123EF931A25751C0A9609C8B63 |work=The New York Times |pages=1\u20132 |accessdate=August 13, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111071844/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE3DE123EF931A25751C0A9609C8B63 |archive-date=November 11, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Earlier the same year, President [[George W. Bush|George Bush]] had named [[North Korea]] as one of three members of the [[Axis of evil|Axis of Evil]], which had upset some South Koreans; directing their anger at Ohno was a less direct way of voicing anger against Bush's decision.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Barbara |last=Demick |author2=Chi Jung Nam |title=Many South Koreans See Skating Loss as Part of U.S. Plot |date=February 26, 2002 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/feb/26/news/mn-29927 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106035119/http://articles.latimes.com/2002/feb/26/news/mn-29927 |archive-date=November 6, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The controversy continued at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]], held jointly in South Korea and Japan several months after the Olympics.<ref name=\"Sports Illustrated\"/> When the South Korean [[Association football|football]] (soccer) team scored a goal against the U.S. team, Korean players [[Ahn Jung-Hwan]] and [[Lee Chun-Soo]] made an exaggerated move imitating the move Ohno had made during the speed skating event to indicate the other athlete had drifted into his lane.<ref name=\"Sports Illustrated\">{{Cite news |title=Korean Hostility |last1=Cazeneuve |first1=Brian |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222133741/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1114728/index.htm |archivedate=February 22, 2014 |date=December 13, 2004 |work=Sports Illustrated |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1114728/index.htm |accessdate=November 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===After Salt Lake===\nOhno continued to perform well in the sport after the 2002 Winter Games. He declined to participate in a 2003 World Cup short-track event in Korea for security reasons.<ref>{{Cite news |first=John |last=Marshall |author2=Vicki Michaelis |title=Korea trip scratched |date=November 22, 2003 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/winter/2003-11-22-ohno-team-withdrawal_x.htm |work=USA Today |accessdate=August 25, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100220163304/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/winter/2003-11-22-ohno-team-withdrawal_x.htm |archive-date=February 20, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite the absence, he successfully defended his World Cup title during the 2003 season.<ref name=\"yahoo profile\"/> He continued his dominance by winning the World Cup title again in the 2004\u20132005 season.<ref name=cup>{{Cite news |title=Winter sports roundup: Ohno takes 3rd World Cup title |date=February 15, 2005 |publisher=Associated Press |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20050213&slug=winter13 |accessdate=November 24, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305185451/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20050213&slug=winter13 |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Saguenay 500m.jpg|thumb|160px|left|alt=A tight group of four skaters leaning inwards as they make a turn.  The four skaters are wearing yellow helmets and suits that the display flag colors of their respective countries.  The skaters have their left hands touching the ice for balance as they accelerate around the turn.|Ohno in lead at a 500&nbsp;meters short-track race at the 2004 World Cup in [[Saguenay, Quebec|Saguenay]]]]\n\nAt the first event of the 2005 World Cup event in China, Ohno severely sprained his ankle and withdrew from the event.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ohno sprains ankle at World Cup meet |date=October 5, 2005 |publisher=The Associated Press |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/winter/2005-10-02-ohno-injured_x.htm |work=USA Today |accessdate=March 18, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208150528/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/winter/2005-10-02-ohno-injured_x.htm |archive-date=December 8, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the second event in South Korea, an estimated 100 riot police stood guard at Incheon International Airport to prevent harm from happening to Ohno.<ref name=\"protection\">{{Cite news |title=Ohno arrives in South Korea |date=October 4, 2005 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2002537989_digs04.html?syndication=rss&source=seattletimes.xml&items=136 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 16, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311015719/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2002537989_digs04.html?syndication=rss&source=seattletimes.xml&items=136 |archivedate=March 11, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> Their concern stemmed from a possible lingering negative reaction from the 2002 Olympic Games disqualification controversy.<ref name=\"protection\"/>\n\nOhno won two gold medals, as well as the overall title at the meet despite suffering from a severe stomach illness,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ohno wins two short-track golds in Seoul |date=October 9, 2005 |publisher=The Associated Press |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/winter/2005-10-09-speedskating-seoul_x.htm |work=USA Today |accessdate=March 18, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208150533/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/winter/2005-10-09-speedskating-seoul_x.htm |archive-date=December 8, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was surprised when the Korean crowd cheered his victories, saying, \"I was really happy with the crowd's reaction. It was pretty positive right from the time we landed. I was really happy it wasn't (hostile). Everything went really smooth. We were happy.\"<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ex-villain Ohno overjoyed with Korean cheers |date=October 12, 2005 |publisher=AFP |url=http://www.mywire.com/pubs/AFP/2005/10/12/1046942?extID=10051 |accessdate=March 18, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529031458/http://www.mywire.com/pubs/AFP/2005/10/12/1046942?extID=10051 |archive-date=May 29, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was unable to defend his World Cup title from the previous three seasons, finishing third in the 2005\u20132006 overall standings.<ref name=\"2006worldcup\">{{Cite news |first=Vicki |last=Michaelis |title=Ohno, Kim lead way for short-track team |date=December 18, 2005 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/winter/2005-12-18-short-track_x.htm |work=USA Today |accessdate=December 22, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080611052527/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/winter/2005-12-18-short-track_x.htm |archive-date=June 11, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[2005 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2005 World Championships]], he finished second overall, winning the 1000&nbsp;m and 3000&nbsp;m races.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Roundup: Ohno wins 2 finals |date=March 14, 2005 |publisher=Associated Press |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20050314&slug=winter14 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 22, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305185912/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20050314&slug=winter14 |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2006 Winter Olympics===\n{{See also|Short track speed skating at the 2006 Winter Olympics }}\nIn the 2006 Winter Olympics in [[Turin, Italy]], Ohno stumbled during a semifinal heat in the 1500&nbsp;m.<ref name=\"stumble\"/> Finishing fifth, he was unable to defend his 2002 gold medal in the event.<ref name=\"stumble\">{{Cite news |title=Ohno fails in attempt to defend 1,500 gold |date=February 27, 2006 |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/11281804/ |publisher=MSNBC |accessdate=August 13, 2009}}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Ohno was able to win the bronze medal in the 1000&nbsp;m, with Korean skaters [[Ahn Hyun Soo]] and [[Lee Ho-suk]] finishing before him.\n\nAfter two false starts from other skaters, Ohno won gold in the 500&nbsp;m when he took the lead with an explosive start and held it until the finish.<ref name=\"torino\"/> Despite criticism that he appeared to move before the start, a violation of the rules, the race start was validated by the officials.<ref name=\"torino\">{{Cite news |first=Bernie |last=Wilson |title=Olympic Short Track Analysis |date=February 25, 2006 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/olympics/torino2006/short_track/news?slug=bw-ohno022506&prov=yhoo&type=lgns |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |accessdate=August 13, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424014122/http://sports.yahoo.com/olympics/torino2006/short_track/news?slug=bw-ohno022506&prov=yhoo&type=lgns |archive-date=April 24, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first=Yi-Wyn |last=Yen |title=Self-starter |date=February 25, 2006 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/olympics/2006/writers/02/25/ohno.reax/index.html |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=August 13, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208134031/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/olympics/2006/writers/02/25/ohno.reax/index.html |archive-date=December 8, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Afterward, Ohno said, \"I was in the moment at the time. I thought I timed the start just perfect. The starter had been pretty quick all day, so that's why there were so many false starts at the beginning. But that was really good for me.\"<ref name=\"torino\"/>\n\nOn the same day as his 500&nbsp;m gold win, he earned a bronze medal in the men's 5000&nbsp;m relay, with an inside pass on Italian skater [[Nicola Rodigari]] on the final leg to put the United States in third position.<ref name=\"torino\"/> Later, during the medals ceremony for the event, the winning South Korean team and the Americans embraced, followed by a group picture featuring the medalists.<ref name=\"msnbc\">{{Cite news |title=Ohno solid gold in 500, finishes with 3 medals |date=February 26, 2006 |url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/11504405// |publisher=MSNBC |pages=2 |accessdate=March 11, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081213165720/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/11504405/ |archive-date=December 13, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Post-Olympic hiatus and return===\nTaking a year off from competitive skating when the 2006 Winter Olympics ended, Ohno returned to win his eighth national title, placing first in every event during the U.S. Championships held from February 23\u201325, 2007.<ref name=\"eight\">{{Cite news |title=Ohno captures 8th national title |date=February 26, 2007 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/othersports/2003589075_winter26.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 12, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701133845/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/othersports/2003589075_winter26.html |archive-date=July 1, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> On April 26, 2007, he was inducted into the Asian Hall of Fame, an award which honors achievements of Asian Americans.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Florangela |last=Davila |title=Asian Hall of Fame inducts Olympian Ohno |date=April 27, 2007 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/othersports/2003683154_ohno27.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 12, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081224155329/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/othersports/2003683154_ohno27.html |archive-date=December 24, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFrom March 9\u201311, 2007, he competed at the [[2007 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2007 World Championships]] held in [[Milan, Italy]], winning gold in the 1500&nbsp;m due to the disqualification of Song Kyung-Taek, who had blocked a passing attempt made by Ohno.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ohno wins via DQ at worlds |date=March 10, 2007 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2003610786_ohno10.html |publisher=The Associated Press |accessdate=August 12, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305185107/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2003610786_ohno10.html |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> He won bronze in the 1000&nbsp;m, 3000&nbsp;m, and the 5000&nbsp;m relay with teammates, Jordan Malone, Travis Jayner, and Ryan Bedford. Because of his wins, he became the overall bronze medalist, behind silver medalist [[Charles Hamelin]] and Ahn Hyun Soo, who became the first man to become a five-time World Champion.<ref name=\"worlds\">{{cite news |first=Bill |last=Beacon |title=Short-track star Charles Hamelin says South Korea still the team to beat despite loss of Ahn Hyun-Soo |date=November 2, 2009 |url=http://www.canadaeast.com/sports/article/844127 |work=The Canadian Press |accessdate=October 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311114419/http://www.canadaeast.com/sports/article/844127 |archive-date=March 11, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2007, in [[Kearns, Utah]], Ohno won his ninth national title, finishing first in the 1000&nbsp;m and the 1500&nbsp;m.<ref name=\"nine\" /> He also finished first in the 500&nbsp;m, but was disqualified for crosstracking.<ref name=\"nine\" /> In the 3000&nbsp;m, he finished second.<ref name=\"nine\">{{Cite news |title=Ohno returns in style, wins 2 finals in Utah |date=December 24, 2007 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/snowsports/2004089541_winter24.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=August 12, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114130942/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/snowsports/2004089541_winter24.html |archive-date=January 14, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[2008 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2008 World Championships]] in [[Gangneung|Gangneung, South Korea]], Ohno won his first overall title, placing first place in the 500&nbsp;m, second in the 1000&nbsp;m, and third place in the 3000&nbsp;m.<ref name=\"world champ\" /> He defeated South Koreans [[Lee Ho-Suk]], silver medalist and Song Kyung-Taek who finished third in points.<ref name=\"world champ\">{{Cite news |title=Ohno speeds to first overall crown at worlds |date=March 10, 2008 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/snowsports/2004271774_winter10.html |work=The Associated Press |accessdate=August 12, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305190222/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/snowsports/2004271774_winter10.html |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, he won his 10th national title and qualified for the world team.<ref name=\"NBC Olympics\" /> Unable to defend his championship, he finished fifth in the overall rankings at the [[2009 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships|2009 World Championships]] in [[Vienna, Austria]], placing second at the 1000&nbsp;m, and winning gold with the 5000&nbsp;m relay team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportresult.com/federations/ISU/ShortTrack/Results.aspx?evt=11210100000030&gen=m&ref=6291&view=rou |title=2009 ISU World Championships, Austria (1000 m finals) |accessdate=August 13, 2009 |publisher=International Skating Union |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412020639/http://www.sportresult.com/federations/ISU/ShortTrack/Results.aspx?evt=11210100000030&gen=m&ref=6291&view=rou |archive-date=April 12, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportresult.com/federations/ISU/ShortTrack/Results.aspx?evt=11210100000030&gen=m&ref=5452&view=dcl |title=2009 ISU World Championships, Austria (5000 m relay finals) |accessdate=August 13, 2009 |publisher=International Skating Union |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525062316/http://www.sportresult.com/federations/ISU/ShortTrack/Results.aspx?evt=11210100000030&gen=m&ref=5452&view=dcl |archive-date=May 25, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2010 Winter Olympics===\n{{See also|Short track speed skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics}}\n\n[[File:2010 Winter Olympics Press Conference.jpg|thumb|right|Closing ceremony press conference at the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] featuring [[Angela Ruggiero]], Ohno, [[Lindsey Vonn]] and [[Bill Demong]]]]\nIn preparation for the [[2010 Winter Olympics]], Ohno lost over {{Convert|9|kg|lbs|abbr=}} from his weight at the 2002 Winter Games.<ref name=\"quest2010\">{{Cite news |first=Kevin |last=Woodley |title=Ohno lightens up in quest for gold |date=February 9, 2010 |url=http://www.teamusa.org/news/2010/02/09/ohno-lightens-up-in-quest-for-gold/31643 |work=Associated Press |accessdate=February 27, 2010 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20100310070914/http://www.teamusa.org/news/2010/02/09/ohno-lightens-up-in-quest-for-gold/31643 |archivedate=March 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He went down to a {{Convert|65.7|kg|lbs|abbr=}} bodyframe and a 2.5% [[body fat percentage]], enduring a 5-month 3-a-day training program combined with a strict nutritional program.<ref name=\"quest2010\"/><ref name=\"career2010\"/> As a result, he could lift double the weight he could before the training.<ref name=\"career2010\"/> With respect to his training regimen, Ohno said: \"Come these Games, there's no one who's going to be fitter than me. There's just no way. Whether I can put it together on the ice or not and feel good, that's a different story. But I know, from a physical training standpoint, nobody's even close... I've never prepared like this in my life\u2014for anything. I want to leave nothing on the table.\"<ref name=\"career2010\">{{Cite news|first=Ron |last=Judd |title=Apolo Ohno savors final chapter in storied Olympics career |date=February 6, 2010 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/olympics/2010986192_ohno07.html |work=Seattle Times |accessdate=February 13, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212105319/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/olympics/2010986192_ohno07.html |archivedate=February 12, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Trials====\nDuring the U.S. Olympic Trials held September 8\u201312, 2009, in [[Marquette, Michigan]], Ohno won the overall meet title and defended his national title.<ref name=\"2009 trials\">{{Cite news |title=Speedskating: Ohno of Seattle takes lead at short-track nationals |date=September 11, 2009 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/othersports/2009850503_digs12.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 14, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918194017/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/othersports/2009850503_digs12.html |archive-date=September 18, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NBC Olympics\"/> He won the finals during the 500&nbsp;m, 1000&nbsp;m, and 1500&nbsp;m races.<ref name=\"2009 trials\"/><ref name=\"narrow victory\"/> However, during the 1000&nbsp;m time trial, Ohno came in second to [[J. R. Celski]] despite skating a personal best of 1:24.500 to Celski's personal best of 1:23.981.<ref name=\"trial times\">{{Cite news |first=Beth |last=Harris |title=Celski outskates Ohno at short track nationals |date=September 9, 2009 |publisher=Associated Press |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2009826633_apolyusshorttrack.html |accessdate=September 14, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305190242/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2009826633_apolyusshorttrack.html |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Celski, who finished second overall and was leading in points after the first two nights of the trials, was injured during a crash in the semifinals of the 1000&nbsp;m race when his right skate sliced into his left leg; he did not skate in the 1000&nbsp;m finals.<ref name=\"Olympic team\"/><ref>{{Cite news |first=Beth |last=Harris |title=Ohno wins 2 events at short track nationals |date=September 12, 2009 |publisher=Associated Press |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2009849900_apolyusshorttrack.html |accessdate=September 14, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310103045/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2009849900_apolyusshorttrack.html |archive-date=March 10, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ohno had a narrow victory in the 500&nbsp;m, beating out the silver place finisher Jeff Simon by only .039 of a second.<ref name=\"narrow victory\">{{Cite news |first=Beth |last=Harris |title=Ohno wins 500 meters _ barely |date=September 13, 2009 |publisher=Associated Press |url=http://www.teamusa.org/news/2009/09/12/ohno-wins-500-meters-_-barely/15915 |accessdate=September 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005183527/http://www.teamusa.org/news/2009/09/12/ohno-wins-500-meters-_-barely/15915 |archivedate=October 5, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Ohno, Celski, [[Jordan Malone]], [[Travis Jayner]], and [[Simon Cho]] were the top five finishers at the trials.<ref name=\"Olympic team\"/> Afterwards, Ohno said of the nominated team: \"This is the strongest team we've ever had. I feel really good about how we will do in the next Olympics.\"<ref name=\"Olympic team\">{{Cite news |first=Jim |last=LaJoie |title=Skater Celski injured in crash at short track Olympic trials |date=September 13, 2009 |work=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2009-09-12-short-track-speedskating_N.htm |accessdate=September 14, 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5t1BbsdJO?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2009-09-12-short-track-speedskating_N.htm |archive-date=September 25, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Games====\nIn the [[Short track speed skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 1500 metres|1500&nbsp;m final]], Ohno placed second after two Korean skaters, [[Lee Ho-Suk]] and [[Sung Si-Bak]], made contact and crashed into the wall during the final turn of the final lap.<ref name=\"20101500m\">{{Cite news |first=H. |last=Darr Beiser |title=Olympic roundup: U.S. captures four medals |date=February 13, 2010 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/vancouver/2010-02-13-olympics-roundup_N.htm |work=USA Today |accessdate=February 14, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217162128/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/vancouver/2010-02-13-olympics-roundup_N.htm |archive-date=February 17, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was in fourth place leading into the crash, and as a result, moved into second place, earning the silver.<ref name=\"20101500m\"/> Fellow American skater [[J. R. Celski]] finished with the bronze medal. The gold medal went to [[South Korea]]'s [[Lee Jung-Su]].<ref name=\"20101500m\"/> This win allowed Ohno, with six career medals, to tie [[Bonnie Blair]] for most medals won by a U.S. Winter Olympian.<ref name=\"20101500m\"/>\n\nHeading into the [[Short track speed skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 1000 metres|1000&nbsp;m final]], Ohno had won the overall silver medal for the 1000&nbsp;m during the [[2009\u201310 Short Track Speed Skating World Cup|2009\u201310 World Cup]] by competing in three of the four competitions during the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportresult.com/federations/ISU/ShortTrack/Results.aspx?evt=11210200000004&gen=m&ref=6372&view=wcl |title=World Cup Classification by Discipline |accessdate=February 17, 2010 |work=International Skating Union |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011165950/http://www.sportresult.com/federations/ISU/ShortTrack/Results.aspx?evt=11210200000004&gen=m&ref=6372&view=wcl |archive-date=October 11, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> During the finals of the 1000&nbsp;m, Ohno finished in third place, making a comeback from a slip with less than three laps remaining.<ref name=\"7medal\">{{Cite news |first=Brian |last=Cazeneuve |title=Medal has Ohno in Seventh Heaven |date=February 21, 2010 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/olympics/2010/writers/brian_cazeneuve/02/21/ohno.seven/ |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100224075640/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/olympics/2010/writers/brian_cazeneuve/02/21/ohno.seven/ |archive-date=February 24, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> With the bronze medal win, he became the most decorated American athlete ever at the Winter Games with seven career medals.<ref name=\"7medal\"/> Bonnie Blair, the former record holder, said she was happy for his accomplishment, adding: \"It's a great feat for him, U.S. speedskating, and the United States of America. We hope that more kids will see his accomplishments and want to try our great sport that has been so good to us and taught us so much about what it takes to be successful in life.\"<ref name=\"7medal\"/>\n\nIn the [[Short track speed skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 500 metres|500&nbsp;m final]], Ohno finished the race in second place behind Canada's [[Charles Hamelin]].<ref name=\"2010500m\">{{Cite news |first=Beth |last=Harris |title=Ohno earns bronze in relay, DQ'd in 500 final |date=February 26, 2010 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2011203713_apolyshoohnosfinale.html |work=Associated Press |accessdate=July 11, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302141858/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2011203713_apolyshoohnosfinale.html |archive-date=March 2, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, he was disqualified after [[Short track speed skating#Rules|impeding]] [[Fran\u00e7ois-Louis Tremblay]] of Canada around the final turn. The silver medal went to [[Sung Si-Bak]], with Tremblay taking the bronze.<ref name=\"2010500m\"/>\n\nThe [[Short track speed skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 5000 metre relay|5000&nbsp;m relay]] team for the United States finished with the bronze medal.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Phil |last=Taylor |title=Record night proves to be just a snapshot of Ohno's entire career |date=February 27, 2010 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/olympics/2010/writers/phil_taylor/02/27/ohno.column/ |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=February 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103132628/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/olympics/2010/writers/phil_taylor/02/27/ohno.column/ |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The team, consisting of [[J. R. Celski]], [[Simon Cho]], [[Travis Jayner]], [[Jordan Malone]], and Ohno, were in the fourth position for the majority of the race.<ref name=\"5000mrelay\">{{Cite news |first=Steve |last=Kelley |title=Ohno helps U.S. take bronze in 5,000 relay |date=February 27, 2010 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/stevekelley/2011204889_kelley27.html |work=Seattle Times |accessdate=February 28, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100228222307/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/stevekelley/2011204889_kelley27.html |archivedate=February 28, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> With a strong push from Celski with two laps to go, Ohno as the [[anchor leg]] was able to pass the Chinese team for third place; Canada won the gold and South Korea took silver.<ref name=\"5000mrelay\"/> This bronze medal was the eighth Olympic medal of his career.<ref name=\"5000mrelay\"/>\n\n===Sponsorships===\n[[File:Speaker Nancy Pelosi Meeting with Shani Davis and Apolo Ohno (4541691200).jpg|thumb|right|In 2010, Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] met with [[Shani Davis]] (left) and Ohno for the B.J. Stupak Scholarship, a federally-funded scholarship program designed to provide financial assistance to Olympic athletes]]\nUsing his recognition and fame from his sport, he has accumulated a list of sponsors that include [[McDonald's]], [[General Electric]], [[The Century Council]], [[Vicks]], and [[Coca-Cola]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Clare |last=Farnsworth |title=Ohno devotes his heart, soul (patch) to Olympics |date=January 21, 2006 |publisher=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/olympics/256503_olympics21.html |accessdate=December 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Olympians Ohno, Vonn among P&G endorsers |date=September 29, 2009 |publisher=Associated Press |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=oly&id=4515804 |accessdate=December 25, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105185541/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=oly&id=4515804 |archive-date=November 5, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first=Tripp |last=Mickle |title=Coke breaks the ice, signs six for Vancouver Olympics |date=May 25, 2009 |publisher=SportsBusiness Journal |url=http://sportsbusinessjournal.com/article/62583 |accessdate=December 26, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090529172400/http://www.sportsbusinessjournal.com/article/62583 |archive-date=May 29, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ohno's father, Yuki, said about sponsorships: \"He's not like a professional athlete who has a multi-million-dollar contract with a team... He has to have sponsorships to pay the bills\".<ref name=\"Alaska\"/> Capitalizing on Ohno's fame, [[Alaska Airlines]] were his primary sponsor for the 2010 Winter Games and designed a [[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-800]] jet with his image on the side.<ref name=\"Alaska\">{{Cite news |first=John |last=Gillie |title=Ohno's image takes off with Alaska |date=November 18, 2009 |publisher=The Olympian |url=http://www.theolympian.com/business/story/1040712.html |accessdate=December 25, 2009 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=Red Director |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"yahoocolbert\">{{Cite news |first=Paul |last=Newberry |title=Ohno not sure why Davis is upset with Colbert |date=December 7, 2009 |publisher=Associated Press |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2010448333_apolyspdcolbertshumor.html |accessdate=December 26, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226181623/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2010448333_apolyspdcolbertshumor.html |archive-date=February 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe was critical of the leaders of the U.S. Speedskating Organization when a donation of $250,000 was raised by viewers of the [[Comedy Central]] show ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' for the organization after their largest commercial sponsor, the Dutch [[DSB Bank]], declared bankruptcy and was unable to donate its $300,000 in November 2009.<ref name=\"yahoocolbert\"/><ref>{{Cite news |first=Vicki |last=Michaelis |title=Colbert fans put up $250,000 for US Speedskating |date=December 7, 2009 |publisher=USA today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/vancouver/speedskating/2009-12-07-colbert-funds_N.htm |accessdate=December 26, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213042522/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/vancouver/speedskating/2009-12-07-colbert-funds_N.htm |archive-date=December 13, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> In an email to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', he wrote it was \"a bit embarrassing that our leadership couldn't secure other sponsors three months before the Olympic Games\" but credited the show's host [[Stephen Colbert (character)|Stephen Colbert]] for \"his willingness to help out our nation's greatest athletes\".<ref name=\"timecolbert\">{{Cite news |first=Sean |last=Gregory |title=Colbert to the Rescue: Can He Save U.S. Speedskating? |date=November 3, 2009 |publisher=Time |url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1934349,00.html?xid=rss-topstories |accessdate=December 26, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091108013620/http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1934349,00.html?xid=rss-topstories |archive-date=November 8, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> In return for ''The Colbert Report'' donation, [[Long track speed skating|long track]] and [[Short track speed skating|short track skaters]] had the \"Colbert Nation\" logo on their uniforms for World Cup events leading up to the 2010 Winter Games.<ref name=\"timecolbert\"/> Ohno did not wear the logo because [[Alaska Airlines]] was his primary sponsor for the 2010 Games.<ref name=\"yahoocolbert\"/> He was also part of [[Oreo]]'s Team DSRL sketch in 2011.\n\n===Retirement===\nOhno retired after the 2010 Olympics and appeared as an NBC commentator for the [[2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Sochi Games]] and [[2018 Winter Olympics|2018 Pyeongchang Games]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Carroll |first=Charlotte |url=https://www.si.com/olympics/2017/11/01/2018-winter-olympics-apolo-ohno-retirement |title=Q&A: Olympic Gold Medalist Apolo Ohno Retirement and 2018 Games |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=November 1, 2017 |accessdate=2019-07-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707103845/https://www.si.com/olympics/2017/11/01/2018-winter-olympics-apolo-ohno-retirement |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2014 Ohno sponsored a speedskating race in Salt Lake City, UT that featured the four top men and women skaters from the US, China, Canada and the Netherlands. He has appeared in a number of television shows as a host, actor and guest star since his retirement.\n\nIn 2019, he was inducted into the [[U.S. Olympic Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.teamusa.org/hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-members |title=U.S. Olympic Hall of Fame |publisher=United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee |accessdate=2019-10-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191114185225/https://www.teamusa.org/hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-members |archive-date=November 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also in 2019, he announced he is writing a book that chronicles his transition from Olympic athlete to entrepreneur.<ref name=\"afterretirement\">{{cite news |url=https://www.teamusa.org/News/2019/May/22/Now-37-Apolo-Ohno-Is-Significantly-Busier-Than-Hes-Ever-Been |title=Now 37, Apolo Ohno Is \"Significantly Busier\" Than He\u2019s Ever Been |work=United States Olympic Committee |date=May 22, 2019 |accessdate=July 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707105346/https://www.teamusa.org/News/2019/May/22/Now-37-Apolo-Ohno-Is-Significantly-Busier-Than-Hes-Ever-Been |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He says the book will \"...pull back the curtain, in a sense, and showcases all the inner workings that go into making an Olympic athlete and then also the other side of what happens after day 17 of the Games when you're no longer competing. You're at the top of your game, you're in top physical condition, top mental condition, and now you're thrust into a world that is very unfamiliar to you and you feel like an alien\".<ref name=\"afterretirement\"/> The book will be released early 2020.<ref name=\"afterretirement\"/>\n\n==Television career==\n[[File:Apolo Anton Ohno 1.JPG|right|thumbnail|alt=A man in a tuxedo is looking down as he signs an autograph on the red carpet. There are people standing in the background.|Ohno at the movie premiere of ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End|Pirates of the Caribbean 3]]''.]]Ohno has had an interest in pursuing a career in the entertainment world.<ref name=\"hollywood\">{{Cite news |first=Steve |last=Ginsburg |title=Olympics-Ohno chooses skating over Hollywood,for now |date=February 16, 2009 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN1244786320090216 |work=Reuters |accessdate=February 23, 2010}}</ref> He participated and won the fourth season of the U.S. reality show ''Dancing with the Stars'' with his partner [[Julianne Hough]]. He returned for the 15th Season which features all-star celebrities. Ohno's interests in fashion led him to be a guest judge on the fashion reality show ''[[Project Runway Season 5#Episode 4: Rings of Glory|Project Runway]]'' in 2008, and to an endorsement deal with [[Omega SA|Omega]], the maker of luxury watches, in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Olympics-Ohno chooses skating over Hollywood,for now'Project Runway' season-five guest judges include Apolo Ohno, Rachel Zoe, RuPaul |date=July 14, 2008 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/fashion/2008/07/project_runways_season_5_guest_1.html |work=New York Magazine |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090319070741/http://nymag.com/daily/fashion/2008/07/project_runways_season_5_guest_1.html |archive-date=March 19, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Omega President Stephen Urquhart said, \"We are very proud to support Apolo here in Vancouver and congratulate him on his outstanding performance. He is poised to make history of his own here and we are thrilled that he is part of the Omega family\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.watchpaper.com/2010/02/14/omega-congratulates-apolo-anton-ohno/ |title=OMEGA congratulates Apolo Anton Ohno |accessdate=March 2, 2010 |date=February 14, 2010 |publisher=Watch Paper |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222050758/http://www.watchpaper.com/2010/02/14/omega-congratulates-apolo-anton-ohno/ |archivedate=February 22, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> He also appeared on ''Minute to Win It'' as the host of the GSN revival in 2013 since he is a fan of the show.<ref name=\"television\">{{Cite news |first=Rob |last=Owen |title=Ohno to host Minute to Win It |date=June 23, 2013 |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/television/2021257191_minutetowinitxml.html |work=Seattle Times |accessdate=September 8, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302195237/http://seattletimes.com/html/television/2021257191_minutetowinitxml.html |archive-date=March 2, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===''Dancing with the Stars''===\n\n'''Season 4 \u2013 with Julianne Hough'''\n\nOhno participated on the [[Dancing with the Stars (US season 4)|fourth season]] of the reality show, ''[[Dancing with the Stars (US TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Ian |last=Ziering |title=Meet the New Cast of 'Dancing With the Stars' |date=February 21, 2007 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Entertainment/story?id=2890554&page=2 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=August 12, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703165434/http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Entertainment/story?id=2890554&page=2 |archive-date=July 3, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was paired with dancing partner [[Julianne Hough]], and both appeared on the show for the first time on March 19, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20062071,00.html |title=Ohno A-Go-Go |accessdate=August 12, 2009 |last=Rizzo |first=Monica |date=April 30, 2007 |work=People |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090603115433/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20062071,00.html |archive-date=June 3, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Together, they received the competition's first perfect score of 30 for their [[samba]] routine on April 16, 2007.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Victor |last=Balta |title=Olympian Ohno scores gold on 'Dancing' |date=April 17, 2007 |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/olympian-ohno-scores-gold-dancing-wbna18142430 |accessdate=August 12, 2009 |publisher=Today.com}}</ref> The dancing duo became finalists in the competition, and went on to become the champions in May 2007.<ref name=\"dwtsPPL\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20039899,00.html |title=Apolo Anton Ohno Wins Dancing with the Stars |accessdate=August 11, 2009 |last=Rizzo |first=Monica |author2=Michelle Tan |date=May 23, 2007 |work=People |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601191225/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20039899,00.html |archive-date=June 1, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"left\"\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" align=\"Center\"|'''Week #'''\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" align=\"Center\"|'''Dance/Song'''\n|colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" align=\"Center\"|'''Judges' score'''\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" align=\"Center\"|'''Result'''\n|-\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|Inaba\n|bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|Goodman\n|bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|Tonioli\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|1\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|[[Cha-cha-cha (dance)|Cha-Cha-Cha]]/ \"[[Let's Hear It for the Boy (song)|Let's Hear It for the Boy]]\"\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|7\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\