=Hawaii Five-O Kupale Full Cast & Crew |publisher=IMDB |access-date=April 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029152816/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2208585/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |archive-date=October 29, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>'' (2012) as a suspect and guest starred in ''[[The Biggest Loser (U.S. TV series)|The Biggest Loser]]'' in Season 12, Episode 9<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2105979/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |title=The Biggest Loser Episode 12.9 Full Cast & Crew |publisher=IMDB |access-date=April 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029152858/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2105979/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |archive-date=October 29, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Season 15, Episode 12.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3451164/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |title=The Biggest Loser Episode 15.12 Full Cast & Crew |publisher=IMDB |access-date=April 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029152452/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3451164/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |archive-date=October 29, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He appeared as the live guest during the season finale of NBC's live variety show ''[[Best Time Ever with Neil Patrick Harris]]'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4181268/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |title=Best Time Ever with Neil Patrick Harris Full Cast & Crew |publisher=IMDB |access-date=April 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919150408/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt4181268/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |archive-date=September 19, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later the following year, Ohno appeared as a guest star on ''[[Hollywood Game Night]]'' hosted by [[Jane Lynch]] on [[NBC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5337670/?ref_=ttep_ep5 |title=Hollywood Game Night-\"Football Game Night\" |publisher=IMDB |access-date=April 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029152715/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5337670/?ref_=ttep_ep5 |archive-date=October 29, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he appeared as a grocery store produce worker on the CBS show [[I Get That a Lot]].\n\nIn 2013, Ohno appeared as the character \"Stone\" in the [[Syfy]] Original Movie ''[[Tasmanian Devils (film)|Tasmanian Devils]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2180543/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |title=Tasmanian Devils Full Cast & Crew |publisher=IMDB |access-date=April 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029152609/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2180543/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |archive-date=October 29, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> as well as the host of [[Game Show Network|GSN]]'s ''[[Minute to Win It]].''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3099134/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |title=Minute To Win It Full Cast & Crew |publisher=IMDB |access-date=April 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029152436/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3099134/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |archive-date=October 29, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2016, he made a guest appearance as himself in an American single-camera sitcom television series ''[[Superstore (TV series)|Superstore]].''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4477976/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=Superstore (2015) Full Cast & Crew |publisher=IMDB |access-date=October 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190310175348/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4477976/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |archive-date=March 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, Ohno appeared as a host in the second season of the reality-competition series ''[[Spartan: Ultimate Team Challenge]]'' the second season premiered on June 12, 2017. In the same year, Ohno appeared on an episode of ''[[Pyramid (game show)|The $100,000 Pyramid]]'' this episode aired on July 9, 2017.\n\n==Personal life and business ventures==\n[[File:Olympic gold medalist Apolo Ohno, 2002 (40171986641).jpg|160px|right|thumbnail|Ohno, after his [[2002 Winter Olympics]] victory, visits the Seattle mayor's office]]After retirement from short track, Ohno began traveling between the U.S and countries in Asia to pursue business in manufacturing, infrastructure development, software and hardware technologies, and health and wellness supplements.<ref name=\"afterretirement\"/> He invested in a Finnish company called Oura Health and is also the cofounder of Allysian Sciences, a health and supplement company.<ref name=\"afterretirement\"/> He is writing a book about his post-skating career that he plans to release early 2020.<ref name=\"afterretirement\"/> He studied business at the [[University of Colorado at Colorado Springs]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rafu.com/dance.html |title=Dancing With Apolo |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |last=Tse |first=Joyce |date=March 24, 2007 |publisher=The Rafu Shimpo |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100220081433/http://www.rafu.com/dance.html |archivedate=February 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe is currently dating Bianca Stam, an actress and restaurant investor.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-apolo-ohno-girlfriend-bianca-stam-20180213-story.html |title=Chicago restaurant investor Bianca Stam dating Apolo Ohno |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=February 13, 2018 |accessdate=July 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707111318/https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-apolo-ohno-girlfriend-bianca-stam-20180213-story.html |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Byx57tUj0G9 |title=Bianca Stam Instagram |last=Stam |first=Bianca |date=June 16, 2019 |accessdate=July 12, 2019 |quote=Thank you for being the best dad to @sesameohno, growing so much constantly and pushing us for the best. You are sesames daddy but you\u2019re also my male constant. Always by my side and never giving up on me, you\u2019re my best friend and love of my life. We love you! @apoloohno }}</ref>\n\nDuring his skating career in the United States, Ohno is credited with popularizing and being the face of his sport.<ref name=\"popular1\">{{Cite news|first=Steve |last=Kelley |title=Other short-track skaters on Apolo Ohno: 'He's our Babe Ruth' |date=February 10, 2010 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/stevekelley/2011027641_kelley10.html |work=Seattle Times |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100213173833/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/stevekelley/2011027641_kelley10.html |archivedate=February 13, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"hollywood\"/> He said it is amazing being able to be role model to younger skaters since growing up, he did not have that influence within his sport, but looked up to other athletes outside his sport, such as [[Muhammad Ali]], [[Joe Frazier]], and [[Lance Armstrong]].<ref name=\"hollywood\"/> After the 2010 Winter Games, he created the Apolo Anton Ohno Foundation and partnered with the [[The Century Council|Century Council]]'s Ask, Listen, Learn Program to discourage [[Legal drinking age|underage drinking]] of [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] and to promote a [[self care|healthy lifestyle]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.asklistenlearn.com/superstars/Apolo |title=Superstars: Apolo Anton Ohno |accessdate=March 9, 2010 |work=Ask, Listen, Learn |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317030525/http://www.asklistenlearn.com/superstars/apolo |archivedate=March 17, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.centurycouncil.org/content/apolo-anton-ohno-partners-century-council-promote-ask-listen-learn-nationwide-0 |title=Apolo Anton Ohno partners with The Century Council to promote 'Ask, Listen, Learn' nationwide |accessdate=March 9, 2010 |date=March 4, 2010 |work=The Century Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305180137/http://www.centurycouncil.org/content/apolo-anton-ohno-partners-century-council-promote-ask-listen-learn-nationwide-0 |archivedate=March 5, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOhno has contributed resources and time being a [[philanthropist]]. He participated in [[Gap (clothing retailer)|GAP]]'s campaign to fight the spread of HIV/AIDS in Africa by joining [[Product Red]].<ref name=\"productred\">{{Cite web |url=http://e-channelnews.com/ec_storydetail.php?ref=413029 |title=Gap (Product) Red Collection designed to make a difference for Africa |accessdate=December 26, 2009 |date=October 9, 2006 |publisher=[[Gap (clothing retailer)|Gap Inc]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061030032530/http://www.e-channelnews.com/ec_storydetail.php?ref=413029 |archivedate=October 30, 2006 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Half of the proceeds went to [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria]].<ref name=\"productred\"/> Besides working with [[The Salvation Army]] and the Clothes off our Back Foundations, he used his fame to help raise funds for a [[Ronald McDonald House]] in Seattle after the 2002 Winter Games.<ref name=\"octospeaker\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.octagonspeakers.com/Default.aspx/Speakers/ApoloAntonOhno |title=Octagon Speakers: Apolo Ohno |accessdate=December 26, 2009 |publisher=The Octagon Speakers Group |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305212340/http://www.octagonspeakers.com/Default.aspx/Speakers/ApoloAntonOhno |archive-date=March 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fhcrc.org/about/pubs/center_news/2002/jun6/br2.html |title=Digging for gold for out-of-town patients |accessdate=June 6, 2002 |publisher=Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906201722/http://www.fhcrc.org/about/pubs/center_news/2002/jun6/br2.html |archive-date=September 6, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> He helped raise $20,000 for Nikkei Concerns, a provider of care and services for Japanese elders living in the [[Pacific Northwest]].<ref name=\"nikkeiconcerns\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nikkeiconcerns.org/pdfs/TAYORI_Fall06.pdf |title=A Winning Evening with Apolo Anton Ohno |accessdate=December 26, 2009 |format=PDF |publisher=Nikkei Concerns |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517032529/http://www.nikkeiconcerns.org/pdfs/TAYORI_Fall06.pdf |archivedate=May 17, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Later that year, Ohno joined Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] to show the importance of math and science education by helping launch the \"Math Moves U Hippest Homework Happening\" program, which gave students the opportunity to do math homework online with celebrities and athletes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raytheon.com/newsroom/feature/hhh06/ |title=MathMovesU makes history with hippest homework happening |accessdate=February 27, 2010 |publisher=Raytheon Company |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114235620/http://www.raytheon.com/newsroom/feature/hhh06/ |archivedate=January 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe has also volunteered with Special Olympics and taken part in Unified Sports, which brings together athletes with intellectual disabilities and without on the same team. Ohno served as a Special Olympics Global Ambassador ahead of the 2015 World Summer Games in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.specialolympics.org/soi/files/resources/AnnualReports/Special_Olympics_2012_Annual_Report-full.pdf |title=Special Olympics 2012 Annual Report |publisher=Special Olympics |date=2012 |accessdate=July 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029152653/http://media.specialolympics.org/soi/files/resources/AnnualReports/Special_Olympics_2012_Annual_Report-full.pdf |archive-date=October 29, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Reflist|group=fn}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n*Ohno, Apolo Anton; Richardson, Nancy A